# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: memory-hierarchy-design
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] In computing, a **cache** (/kæʃ/ ⓘ *KASH*) is a hardware or software component that stores data so that future requests for that data can be served faster; the data stored in a cache might be the result of an earlier computation or a copy of data stored elsewhere.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] A **cache hit** occurs when the requested data can be found in a cache, while a **cache miss** occurs when it cannot.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] Cache hits are served by reading data from the cache, which is faster than recomputing a result or reading from a slower data store; thus, the more requests that can be served from the cache, the faster the system performs.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] To be cost-effective, caches must be relatively small.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] Nevertheless, caches are effective in many areas of computing because typical computer applications access data with a high degree of locality of reference.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] Such access patterns exhibit temporal locality, where data is requested that has been recently requested, and spatial locality, where data is requested that is stored near data that has already been requested.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] In memory design, there is an inherent trade-off between capacity and speed because larger capacity implies larger size and thus greater physical distances for signals to travel causing propagation delays.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] There is also a tradeoff between high-performance technologies such as SRAM and cheaper, easily mass-produced commodities such as DRAM, flash, or hard disks.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] The buffering provided by a cache benefits one or both of latency and throughput (bandwidth).
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] A larger resource incurs a significant latency for access – e.g. it can take hundreds of clock cycles for a modern 4 GHz processor to reach DRAM.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] This is mitigated by reading large chunks into the cache, in the hope that subsequent reads will be from nearby locations and can be read from the cache.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] Prediction or explicit prefetching can be used to guess where future reads will come from and make requests ahead of time; if done optimally, the latency is bypassed altogether.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] The use of a cache also allows for higher throughput from the underlying resource, by assembling multiple fine-grain transfers into larger, more efficient requests.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] In the case of DRAM circuits, the additional throughput may be gained by using a wider data bus.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] Hardware implements cache as a block of memory for temporary storage of data likely to be used again.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] Central processing units (CPUs), solid-state drives (SSDs) and hard disk drives (HDDs) frequently include hardware-based cache, while web browsers and web servers commonly rely on software caching.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] A cache is made up of a pool of entries.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] Each entry has associated *data*, which is a copy of the same data in some *backing store*.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] Each entry also has a *tag*, which specifies the identity of the data in the backing store of which the entry is a copy.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] When the cache client (a CPU, web browser, operating system) needs to access data presumed to exist in the backing store, it first checks the cache.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] If an entry can be found with a tag matching that of the desired data, the data in the entry is used instead.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] This situation is known as a **cache hit**.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] For example, a web browser program might check its local cache on disk to see if it has a local copy of the contents of a web page at a particular URL.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] In this example, the URL is the tag, and the content of the web page is the data.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] The percentage of accesses that result in cache hits is known as the **hit rate** or **hit ratio** of the cache.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] The alternative situation, when the cache is checked and found not to contain any entry with the desired tag, is known as a **cache miss**.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] This requires a more expensive access of data from the backing store.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] Once the requested data is retrieved, it is typically copied into the cache, ready for the next access.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] During a cache miss, some other previously existing cache entry is typically removed in order to make room for the newly retrieved data.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] The heuristic used to select the entry to replace is known as the replacement policy.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] One popular replacement policy, least recently used (LRU), replaces the oldest entry, the entry that was accessed less recently than any other entry.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] More sophisticated caching algorithms also take into account the frequency of use of entries.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] Cache writes must eventually be propagated to the backing store.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] The timing for this is governed by the *write policy*.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] A write-back cache is more complex to implement since it needs to track which of its locations have been written over and mark them as *dirty* for later writing to the backing store.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] The data in these locations are written back to the backing store only when they are evicted from the cache, a process referred to as a *lazy write*.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] For this reason, a read miss in a write-back cache may require two memory accesses to the backing store: one to write back the dirty data, and one to retrieve the requested data.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] Other policies may also trigger data write-back.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] The client may make many changes to data in the cache, and then explicitly notify the cache to write back the data.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] Consequently, a decision needs to be made for write misses: whether or not to load the data into the cache.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] Entities other than the cache may change the data in the backing store, in which case the copy in the cache may become out-of-date or *stale*.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] Alternatively, when the client updates the data in the cache, copies of that data in other caches will become stale.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] Communication protocols between the cache managers that keep the data consistent are associated with cache coherence.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] On a cache read miss, caches with a *demand paging policy* read the minimum amount from the backing store.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] A typical demand-paging virtual memory implementation reads one page of virtual memory (often 4 KB) from disk into the disk cache in RAM.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] A typical CPU reads a single L2 cache line of 128 bytes from DRAM into the L2 cache, and a single L1 cache line of 64 bytes from the L2 cache into the L1 cache.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] Caches with a prefetch input queue or more general *anticipatory paging policy* go further—they not only read the data requested, but guess that the next chunk or two of data will soon be required, and so prefetch that data into the cache ahead of time.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] Anticipatory paging is especially helpful when the backing store has a long latency to read the first chunk and much shorter times to sequentially read the next few chunks, such as disk storage and DRAM.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] A few operating systems go further with a loader that always pre-loads the entire executable into RAM.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] A few caches go even further, not only pre-loading an entire file, but also starting to load other related files that may soon be requested, such as the page cache associated with a prefetcher or the web cache associated with link prefetching.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] Small memories on or close to the CPU can operate faster than the much larger main memory.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] Most CPUs since the 1980s have used one or more caches, sometimes in cascaded levels; modern high-end embedded, desktop and server microprocessors may have as many as six types of cache (between levels and functions).
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] Some examples of caches with a specific function are the D-cache, I-cache and the translation lookaside buffer for the memory management unit (MMU).
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] Earlier graphics processing units (GPUs) often had limited read-only texture caches and used swizzling to improve 2D locality of reference.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] Cache misses would drastically affect performance, e.g. if mipmapping was not used.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] Caching was important to leverage 32-bit (and wider) transfers for texture data that was often as little as 4 bits per pixel.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] As GPUs advanced, supporting general-purpose computing on graphics processing units and compute kernels, they have developed progressively larger and increasingly general caches, including instruction caches for shaders, exhibiting functionality commonly found in CPU caches.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] These caches have grown to handle synchronization primitives between threads and atomic operations, and interface with a CPU-style MMU.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] Digital signal processors have similarly generalized over the years.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] Earlier designs used scratchpad memory fed by direct memory access; modern DSPs often include a very similar set of caches to a CPU (e.g.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] Modified Harvard architecture with shared L2, split L1 I-cache and D-cache).
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] A memory management unit (MMU) that fetches page table entries from main memory has a specialized cache, used for recording the results of virtual address to physical address translations.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] This specialized cache is called a translation lookaside buffer (TLB).
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] Information-centric networking (ICN) is an approach to evolve the Internet infrastructure away from a host-centric paradigm, based on perpetual connectivity and the end-to-end principle, to a network architecture in which the focal point is identified information.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] Due to the inherent caching capability of the nodes in an ICN, it can be viewed as a loosely connected network of caches, which has unique requirements for caching policies.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] However, ubiquitous content caching introduces the challenge to content protection against unauthorized access, which requires extra care and solutions.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] Unlike proxy servers, in ICN the cache is a network-level solution.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] Therefore, it has rapidly changing cache states and higher request arrival rates; moreover, smaller cache sizes impose different requirements on the content eviction policies.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] In particular, eviction policies for ICN should be fast and lightweight.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] Various cache replication and eviction schemes for different ICN architectures and applications have been proposed.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] The time aware least recently used (TLRU) is a variant of LRU designed for the situation where the stored contents in cache have a valid lifetime.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] The algorithm is suitable in network cache applications, such as ICN, content delivery networks (CDNs) and distributed networks in general.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] TLRU introduces a new term: time to use (TTU).
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] TTU is a time stamp on content which stipulates the usability time for the content based on the locality of the content and information from the content publisher.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] Owing to this locality-based time stamp, TTU provides more control to the local administrator to regulate in-network storage.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] In the TLRU algorithm, when a piece of content arrives, a cache node calculates the local TTU value based on the TTU value assigned by the content publisher.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] The local TTU value is calculated by using a locally defined function.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] Once the local TTU value is calculated the replacement of content is performed on a subset of the total content stored in cache node.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] The TLRU ensures that less popular and short-lived content should be replaced with incoming content.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] The least frequent recently used (LFRU) cache replacement scheme combines the benefits of LFU and LRU schemes.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] LFRU is suitable for network cache applications, such as ICN, CDNs and distributed networks in general.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] In LFRU, the cache is divided into two partitions called privileged and unprivileged partitions.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] The privileged partition can be seen as a protected partition.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] If content is highly popular, it is pushed into the privileged partition.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] Replacement of the privileged partition is done by first evicting content from the unprivileged partition, then pushing content from the privileged partition to the unprivileged partition, and finally inserting new content into the privileged partition.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] In the above procedure, the LRU is used for the privileged partition and an approximated LFU (ALFU) scheme is used for the unprivileged partition.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] The basic idea is to cache the locally popular content with the ALFU scheme and push the popular content to the privileged partition.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] In 2011, the use of smartphones with weather forecasting options was overly taxing AccuWeather servers; two requests from the same area would generate separate requests.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] An optimization by edge-servers to truncate the GPS coordinates to fewer decimal places meant that the cached results from a nearby query would be used.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] The number of to-the-server lookups per day dropped by half.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] While CPU caches are generally managed entirely by hardware, a variety of software manages other caches.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] The page cache in main memory is managed by the operating system kernel.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] While the disk buffer, which is an integrated part of the hard disk drive or solid state drive, is sometimes misleadingly referred to as *disk cache*, its main functions are write sequencing and read prefetching.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] High-end disk controllers often have their own on-board cache for the hard disk drive's data blocks.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] Finally, a fast local hard disk drive can also cache information held on even slower data storage devices, such as remote servers (web cache) or local tape drives or optical jukeboxes; such a scheme is the main concept of hierarchical storage management.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] Also, fast flash-based solid-state drives (SSDs) can be used as caches for slower rotational-media hard disk drives, working together as hybrid drives.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] Web browsers and web proxy servers, either locally or at the Internet service provider (ISP), employ web caches to store previous responses from web servers, such as web pages and images.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] Web caches reduce the amount of information that needs to be transmitted across the network, as information previously stored in the cache can often be re-used.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] This reduces bandwidth and processing requirements of the web server, and helps to improve responsiveness for users of the web.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] Another form of cache is P2P caching, where the files most sought for by peer-to-peer applications are stored in an ISP cache to accelerate P2P transfers.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] Similarly, decentralised equivalents exist, which allow communities to perform the same task for P2P traffic, for example, Corelli.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] A cache can store data that is computed on demand rather than retrieved from a backing store.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] Memoization is an optimization technique that stores the results of resource-consuming function calls within a lookup table, allowing subsequent calls to reuse the stored results and avoid repeated computation.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] It is related to the dynamic programming algorithm design methodology, which can also be thought of as a means of caching.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] A content delivery network (CDN) is a network of distributed servers that deliver pages and other web content to a user, based on the geographic locations of the user, the origin of the web page and the content delivery server.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] CDNs were introduced in the late 1990s as a way to speed up the delivery of static content, such as HTML pages, images and videos.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] By replicating content on multiple servers around the world and delivering it to users based on their location, CDNs can significantly improve the speed and availability of a website or application.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] When a user requests a piece of content, the CDN will check to see if it has a copy of the content in its cache.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] If it does, the CDN will deliver the content to the user from the cache.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] A cloud storage gateway is a hybrid cloud storage device that connects a local network to one or more cloud storage services, typically object storage services such as Amazon S3.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] It provides a cache for frequently accessed data, providing high speed local access to frequently accessed data in the cloud storage service.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] Cloud storage gateways also provide additional benefits such as accessing cloud object storage through traditional file serving protocols as well as continued access to cached data during connectivity outages.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] A DNS cache caches a mapping of domain names to IP addresses.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] Examples of services providing such caches include the BIND daemon and caching DNS resolver libraries.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] Write-through operation is common when operating over unreliable networks, because of the enormous complexity of the coherency protocol required between multiple write-back caches when communication is unreliable.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] For instance, web page caches and client-side caches for distributed file systems (like those in NFS or SMB) are typically read-only or write-through specifically to keep the network protocol simple and reliable.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] Web search engines also frequently make web pages they have indexed available from their cache.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] This can prove useful when web pages from a web server are temporarily or permanently inaccessible.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] Database caching can substantially improve the throughput of database applications, for example in the processing of indexes, data dictionaries, and frequently used subsets of data.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] A distributed cache uses networked hosts to provide scalability, reliability and performance to the application.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] The hosts can be co-located or spread over different geographical regions.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] Android Runtime and Common Language Runtime are examples that utilize storage-based JIT caches.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] GPU drivers usually utilize storage-based shader caches.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] The semantics of a *buffer* and a *cache* are not totally different; even so, there are fundamental differences in intent between the process of caching and the process of buffering.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] Fundamentally, caching realizes a performance increase for transfers of data that is being repeatedly transferred.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] With read caches, a data item must have been fetched from its residing location at least once in order for subsequent reads of the data item to realize a performance increase by virtue of being able to be fetched from the cache's faster intermediate storage rather than the data's residing location.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] Contrary to strict buffering, a caching process must adhere to a potentially distributed cache coherency protocol in order to maintain consistency between the cache's intermediate storage and the location where the data resides.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] Buffering, on the other hand, reduces the number of transfers for otherwise novel data amongst communicating processes, which amortizes the overhead involved for several small transfers over fewer, larger transfers.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] It also provides an intermediary for communicating processes that are incapable of direct transfers amongst each other, or ensures a minimum data size or representation required by at least one of the communicating processes involved in a transfer.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] With typical caching implementations, a data item that is read or written for the first time is effectively being buffered.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] Caching almost always involves some form of buffering, while strict buffering does not necessarily involve caching.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] A buffer is a temporary memory location that is traditionally used because CPU instructions cannot directly address data stored in peripheral devices.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] Thus, addressable memory is used as an intermediate stage.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] Additionally, such a buffer may be required when a large block of data is assembled or disassembled (as required by a storage device), or when data may be delivered in a different order than that in which it is produced.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] Also, a whole buffer of data is usually transferred sequentially (for example, to hard disk), so buffering itself sometimes increases transfer performance or reduces the variation or jitter of the transfer's latency as opposed to caching where the intent is to reduce the latency.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] These benefits are present even if the buffered data are written to the buffer once and read from the buffer once.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] A cache also increases transfer performance.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] A part of the increase similarly comes from the possibility that multiple small transfers will be combined into one large transfer.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] But the main performance gain occurs because there is a good chance that the same data will be read from cache multiple times, or that written data will soon be read.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] A cache's sole purpose is to reduce accesses to the underlying slower storage.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-computing] Cache is also usually an abstraction layer that is designed to be invisible from the perspective of neighboring layers.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] In computing, **cache replacement policies** (also known as **cache replacement algorithms** or **cache algorithms**) are optimizing instructions or algorithms which a computer program or hardware-maintained structure can utilize to manage a cache of information.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] Caching improves performance by keeping recent or often-used data items in memory locations which are faster, or computationally cheaper to access, than normal memory stores.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] When the cache is full, the algorithm must choose which items to discard to make room for new data.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] A cache has two primary figures of merit: latency and hit ratio.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] A number of secondary factors also affect cache performance.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] The hit ratio of a cache describes how often a searched-for item is found.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] More efficient replacement strategies track more usage information to improve the hit rate for a given cache size.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] The latency of a cache describes how long after requesting a desired item the cache can return that item when there is a hit.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] Faster replacement strategies typically track less usage information—or, with a direct-mapped cache, no information—to reduce the time required to update the information.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] Each replacement strategy is a compromise between hit rate and latency.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] Hit-rate measurements are typically performed on benchmark applications, and the hit ratio varies by application.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] Video and audio streaming applications often have a hit ratio near zero, because each bit of data in the stream is read once (a compulsory miss), used, and then never read or written again.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] Many cache algorithms (particularly LRU) allow streaming data to fill the cache, pushing out information which will soon be used again (cache pollution).
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] Other factors may be size, length of time to obtain, and expiration.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] Depending on cache size, no further caching algorithm to discard items may be needed.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] Algorithms also maintain cache coherence when several caches are used for the same data, such as multiple database servers updating a shared data file.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] The most efficient caching algorithm would be to discard information which would not be needed for the longest time; this is known as Bélády's optimal algorithm, optimal replacement policy, or the clairvoyant algorithm.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] Since it is generally impossible to predict how far in the future information will be needed, this is unfeasible in practice.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] The practical minimum can be calculated after experimentation, and the effectiveness of a chosen cache algorithm can be compared.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] When a page fault occurs, a set of pages is in memory.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] In the example, the sequence of 5, 0, 1 is accessed by Frame 1, Frame 2, and Frame 3 respectively.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] When 2 is accessed, it replaces value 5 (which is in frame 1, predicting that value 5 will not be accessed in the near future.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] Because a general-purpose operating system cannot predict when 5 will be accessed, Bélády's algorithm cannot be implemented there.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] Random replacement selects an item and discards it to make space when necessary.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] This algorithm does not require keeping any access history.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] It has been used in ARM processors due to its simplicity, and it allows efficient stochastic simulation.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] With this algorithm, the cache behaves like a FIFO queue; it evicts blocks in the order in which they were added, regardless of how often or how many times they were accessed before.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] The cache behaves like a stack, and unlike a FIFO queue.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] The cache evicts the block added most recently first, regardless of how often or how many times it was accessed before.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] Discards least recently used items first.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] This algorithm requires keeping track of what was used and when, which is cumbersome.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] It requires "age bits" for cache lines, and tracks the least recently used cache line based on these age bits.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] When a cache line is used, the age of the other cache lines changes.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] LRU is a family of caching algorithms, that includes 2Q by Theodore Johnson and Dennis Shasha and LRU/K by Pat O'Neil, Betty O'Neil and Gerhard Weikum.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] When A B C D is installed in the blocks with sequence numbers (increment 1 for each new access) and E is accessed, it is a miss and must be installed in a block.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] With the LRU algorithm, E will replace A because A has the lowest rank (A(0)).
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] In the next-to-last step, D is accessed and the sequence number is updated.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] F is then accessed, replacing B – which had the lowest rank, (B(1)).
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] Time-aware, least recently used (TLRU) is a variant of LRU designed for when the contents of a cache have a valid lifetime.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] The algorithm is suitable for network cache applications such as information-centric networking (ICN), content delivery networks (CDNs) and distributed networks in general.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] TLRU introduces a term: TTU (time to use), a timestamp of content (or a page) that stipulates the usability time for the content based on its locality and the content publisher.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] TTU provides more control to a local administrator in regulating network storage.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] When content subject to TLRU arrives, a cache node calculates the local TTU based on the TTU assigned by the content publisher.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] The local TTU value is calculated with a locally defined function.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] When the local TTU value is calculated, content replacement is performed on a subset of the total content of the cache node.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] TLRU ensures that less-popular and short-lived content is replaced with incoming content.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] Unlike LRU, MRU discards the most recently used items first.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] MRU algorithms are most useful in situations where the older an item is, the more likely it is to be accessed.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] A B C D are placed in the cache, since there is space available.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] At the fifth access (E), the block which held D is replaced with E since this block was used most recently.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] At the next access (to D), C is replaced since it was the block accessed just before D.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] An SLRU cache is divided into two segments: probationary and protected.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] Lines in each segment are ordered from most- to least-recently-accessed.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] Data from misses is added to the cache at the most-recently-accessed end of the probationary segment.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] Hits are removed from where they reside and added to the most-recently-accessed end of the protected segment; lines in the protected segment have been accessed at least twice.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] The size limit of the protected segment is an SLRU parameter which varies according to I/O workload patterns.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] When data must be discarded from the cache, lines are obtained from the LRU end of the probationary segment.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] LRU may be expensive in caches with higher associativity.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] Practical hardware usually employs an approximation to achieve similar performance at a lower hardware cost.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] For CPU caches with large associativity (generally > four ways), the implementation cost of LRU becomes prohibitive.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] In many CPU caches, an algorithm that almost always discards one of the least recently used items is sufficient; many CPU designers choose a PLRU algorithm, which only needs one bit per cache item to work.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] PLRU typically has a slightly-worse miss ratio, slightly-better latency, uses slightly less power than LRU, and has a lower overhead than LRU.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] Bits work as a binary tree of one-bit pointers which point to a less-recently-used sub-tree.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] Following the pointer chain to the leaf node identifies the replacement candidate.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] With an access, all pointers in the chain from the accessed way's leaf node to the root node are set to point to a sub-tree which does not contain the accessed path.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] When there is access to a value (such as A) and it is not in the cache, it is loaded from memory and placed in the block where the arrows are pointing in the example.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] After that block is placed, the arrows are flipped to point the opposite way.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] A, B, C and D are placed; E replaces A as the cache fills because that was where the arrows were pointing, and the arrows which led to A flip to point in the opposite direction (to B, the block which will be replaced on the next cache miss).
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] The LRU algorithm cannot be implemented in the critical path of computer systems, such as operating systems, due to its high overhead; Clock, an approximation of LRU, is commonly used instead.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] Clock-Pro is an approximation of LIRS for low-cost implementation in systems.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] Clock-Pro has the basic Clock framework, with three advantages.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] It has three "clock hands" (unlike Clock's single "hand"), and can approximately measure the reuse distance of data accesses.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] Like LIRS, it can quickly evict one-time-access or low-locality data items.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] Clock-Pro is as complex as Clock, and is easy to implement at low cost.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] The buffer-cache replacement implementation in the 2017 version of Linux combines LRU and Clock-Pro.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] The LFU algorithm counts how often an item is needed; those used less often are discarded first.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] This is similar to LRU, except that how many times a block was accessed is stored instead of how recently.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] While running an access sequence, the block which was used the fewest times will be removed from the cache.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] The least frequent recently used (LFRU) algorithm combines the benefits of LFU and LRU.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] LFRU is suitable for network cache applications such as ICN, CDNs, and distributed networks in general.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] In LFRU, the cache is divided into two partitions: privileged and unprivileged.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] The privileged partition is protected; if content is popular, it is pushed into the privileged partition.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] In replacing the privileged partition, LFRU evicts content from the unprivileged partition; pushes content from the privileged to the unprivileged partition, and inserts new content into the privileged partition.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] LRU is used for the privileged partition and an approximated LFU (ALFU) algorithm for the unprivileged partition.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] A variant, LFU with dynamic aging (LFUDA), uses dynamic aging to accommodate shifts in a set of popular objects; it adds a cache-age factor to the reference count when a new object is added to the cache or an existing object is re-referenced.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] LFUDA increments cache age when evicting blocks by setting it to the evicted object's key value, and the cache age is always less than or equal to the minimum key value in the cache.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] If an object was frequently accessed in the past and becomes unpopular, it will remain in the cache for a long time (preventing newly- or less-popular objects from replacing it).
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] Dynamic aging reduces the number of such objects, making them eligible for replacement, and LFUDA reduces cache pollution caused by LFU when a cache is small.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] This is a new eviction algorithm designed in 2023.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] Compared to existing algorithms, which mostly build on LRU (least-recently-used), S3-FIFO only uses three FIFO queues: a small queue occupying 10% of cache space, a main queue that uses 90% of the cache space, and a ghost queue that only stores object metadata.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] RRIP-style policies are the basis for other cache replacement policies, including Hawkeye.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] RRIP is a flexible policy, proposed by Intel, which attempts to provide good scan resistance while allowing older cache lines that have not been reused to be evicted.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] All cache lines have a prediction value, the RRPV (re-reference prediction value), that should correlate with when the line is expected to be reused.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] The RRPV is usually high on insertion; if a line is not reused soon, it will be evicted to prevent scans (large amounts of data used only once) from filling the cache.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] When a cache line is reused the RRPV is set to zero, indicating that the line has been reused once and is likely to be reused again.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] On a cache miss, the line with an RRPV equal to the maximum possible RRPV is evicted; with 3-bit values, a line with an RRPV of 23 - 1 = 7 is evicted.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] If no lines have this value, all RRPVs in the set are increased by 1 until one reaches it.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] A tie-breaker is needed, and usually, it is the first line on the left.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] The increase is needed to ensure that older lines are aged properly and will be evicted if they are not reused.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] SRRIP inserts lines with an RRPV value of maxRRPV; a line which has just been inserted will be the most likely to be evicted on a cache miss.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] SRRIP performs well normally, but suffers when the working set is much larger than the cache size and causes cache thrashing.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] This is remedied by inserting lines with an RRPV value of maxRRPV most of the time, and inserting lines with an RRPV value of maxRRPV - 1 randomly with a low probability.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] This causes some lines to "stick" in the cache, and helps prevent thrashing.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] BRRIP degrades performance, however, on non-thrashing accesses.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] SRRIP performs best when the working set is smaller than the cache, and BRRIP performs best when the working set is larger than the cache.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] DRRIP uses set dueling to select whether to use SRRIP or BRRIP.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] It dedicates a few sets (typically 32) to use SRRIP and another few to use BRRIP, and uses a policy counter which monitors set performance to determine which policy will be used by the rest of the cache.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] Bélády's algorithm is the optimal cache replacement policy, but it requires knowledge of the future to evict lines that will be reused farthest in the future.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] A number of replacement policies have been proposed which attempt to predict future reuse distances from past access patterns, allowing them to approximate the optimal replacement policy.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] Some of the best-performing cache replacement policies attempt to imitate Bélády's algorithm.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] Hawkeye attempts to emulate Bélády's algorithm by using past accesses by a PC to predict whether the accesses it produces generate cache-friendly (used later) or cache-averse accesses (not used later).
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] It samples a number of non-aligned cache sets, uses a history of length $8\times {\text{the cache size}}$ and emulates Bélády's algorithm on these accesses.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] This allows the policy to determine which lines should have been cached and which should not, predicting whether an instruction is cache-friendly or cache-averse.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] This data is then fed into an RRIP; accesses from cache-friendly instructions have a lower RRPV value (likely to be evicted later), and accesses from cache-averse instructions have a higher RRPV value (likely to be evicted sooner).
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] The RRIP backend makes the eviction decisions.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] The sampled cache and OPT generator set the initial RRPV value of the inserted cache lines.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] Hawkeye won the CRC2 cache championship in 2017, and Harmony is an extension of Hawkeye which improves prefetching performance.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] Mockingjay tries to improve on Hawkeye in several ways.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] It drops the binary prediction, allowing it to make more fine-grained decisions about which cache lines to evict, and leaves the decision about which cache line to evict for when more information is available.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] Mockingjay keeps a sampled cache of unique accesses, the PCs that produced them, and their timestamps.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] When a line in the sampled cache is accessed again, the time difference will be sent to the reuse distance predictor.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] The RDP uses temporal difference learning, where the new RDP value will be increased or decreased by a small number to compensate for outliers; the number is calculated as $w=\min \left(1,{\frac {\text{timestamp difference}}{16}}\right)$ .
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] If the value has not been initialized, the observed reuse distance is inserted directly.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] If the sampled cache is full and a line needs to be discarded, the RDP is instructed that the PC that last accessed it produces streaming accesses.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] On an access or insertion, the estimated time of reuse (ETR) for this line is updated to reflect the predicted reuse distance.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] On a cache miss, the line with the highest ETR value is evicted.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] Mockingjay has results which are close to the optimal Bélády's algorithm.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] A number of policies have attempted to use perceptrons, markov chains or other types of machine learning to predict which line to evict.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] Learning augmented algorithms also exist for cache replacement.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] LIRS is a page replacement algorithm with better performance than LRU and other, newer replacement algorithms.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] Reuse distance is a metric for dynamically ranking accessed pages to make a replacement decision.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] LIRS addresses the limits of LRU by using recency to evaluate inter-reference recency (IRR) to make a replacement decision.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] In the diagram, X indicates that a block is accessed at a particular time.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] If block A1 is accessed at time 1, its recency will be 0; this is the first-accessed block and the IRR will be 1, since it predicts that A1 will be accessed again in time 3.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] In time 2, since A4 is accessed, the recency will become 0 for A4 and 1 for A1; A4 is the most recently accessed object, and the IRR will become 4.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] At time 10, the LIRS algorithm will have two sets: an LIR set = {A1, A2} and an HIR set = {A3, A4, A5}.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] At time 10, if there is access to A4 a miss occurs; LIRS will evict A5 instead of A2 because of its greater recency.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] Adaptive replacement cache (ARC) constantly balances between LRU and LFU to improve the combined result.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] It improves SLRU by using information about recently evicted cache items to adjust the size of the protected and probationary segments to make the best use of available cache space.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] Clock with adaptive replacement (CAR) combines the advantages of ARC and Clock.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] CAR performs comparably to ARC, and outperforms LRU and Clock.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] Like ARC, CAR is self-tuning and requires no user-specified parameters.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] The multi-queue replacement (MQ) algorithm was developed to improve the performance of a second-level buffer cache, such as a server buffer cache, and was introduced in a paper by Zhou, Philbin, and Li.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] The MQ cache contains an *m* number of LRU queues: Q0, Q1, ..., Q*m*-1.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] The value of *m* represents a hierarchy based on the lifetime of all blocks in that queue.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] Pannier is a container-based flash caching mechanism which identifies containers whose blocks have variable access patterns.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] Pannier has a priority-queue-based survival-queue structure to rank containers based on their survival time, which is proportional to live data in the container.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] Static analysis determines which accesses are cache hits or misses to indicate the worst-case execution time of a program.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] An approach to analyzing properties of LRU caches is to give each block in the cache an "age" (0 for the most recently used) and compute intervals for possible ages.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] This analysis can be refined to distinguish cases where the same program point is accessible by paths that result in misses or hits.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] An efficient analysis may be obtained by abstracting sets of cache states by antichains which are represented by compact binary decision diagrams.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] LRU static analysis does not extend to pseudo-LRU policies.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cache-replacement-policies] According to computational complexity theory, static-analysis problems posed by pseudo-LRU and FIFO are in higher complexity classes than those for LRU.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] A **CPU cache** is a hardware cache used by the central processing unit (CPU) of a computer to reduce the average cost (time or energy) to access data from the main memory.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] A cache is a smaller, faster memory, located closer to a processor core, which stores copies of the data from frequently used main memory locations, avoiding the need to always refer to main memory which may be tens to hundreds of times slower to access.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] Cache memory is typically implemented with static random-access memory (SRAM), which requires multiple transistors to store a single bit.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] This makes it expensive in terms of the area it takes up, and in modern CPUs the cache is typically the largest part by chip area.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] The size of the cache needs to be balanced with the general desire for smaller chips which cost less.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] Some modern designs implement some or all of their cache using the physically smaller eDRAM, which is slower to use than SRAM but allows larger amounts of cache for any given amount of chip area.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] Most CPUs have a hierarchy of multiple cache levels (L1, L2, often L3, and rarely even L4), with separate instruction-specific (I-cache) and data-specific (D-cache) caches at level 1.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] The different levels are implemented in different areas of the chip; L1 is located as close to a CPU core as possible and thus offers the highest speed due to short signal paths, but requires careful design.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] L2 caches are physically separate from the CPU and operate slower, but place fewer demands on the chip designer and can be made much larger without impacting the CPU design.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] L3 caches are generally shared among multiple CPU cores.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] Other types of caches exist (that are not counted towards the "cache size" of the most important caches mentioned above), such as the translation lookaside buffer (TLB) which is part of the memory management unit (MMU) which most CPUs have.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] Input/output sections also often contain data buffers that serve a similar purpose.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] To access data in main memory, a multi-step process is used and each step introduces a delay.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] For instance, to read a value from memory in a simple computer system the CPU first selects the address to be accessed by expressing it on the address bus and waiting a fixed time to allow the value to settle.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] The memory device with that value, normally implemented in DRAM, holds that value in a very low-energy form that is not powerful enough to be read directly by the CPU.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] Instead, it has to copy that value from storage into a small buffer which is connected to the data bus.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] It then waits a certain time to allow this value to settle before reading the value from the data bus.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] By locating the memory physically closer to the CPU the time needed for the buses to settle is reduced, and by replacing the DRAM with SRAM, which hold the value in a form that does not require amplification to be read, the delay within the memory itself is eliminated.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] This makes the cache much faster both to respond and to read or write.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] SRAM, however, requires anywhere from four to six transistors to hold a single bit, depending on the type, whereas DRAM generally uses one transistor and one capacitor per bit, which makes it able to store much more data for any given chip area.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] Implementing some memory in a faster format can lead to large performance improvements.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] When trying to read from or write to a location in the memory, the processor checks whether the data from that location is already in the cache.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] If so, the processor will read from or write to the cache instead of the much slower main memory.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] Used to speed up virtual-to-physical address translation for both executable instructions and data.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] A single TLB can be provided for access to both instructions and data, or a separate Instruction TLB (ITLB) and data TLB (DTLB) can be provided.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] (MMU) and not directly related to the CPU caches.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] Early examples of CPU caches include the Atlas 2 and the IBM System/360 Model 85 in the 1960s.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] The first CPUs that used a cache had only one level of cache; unlike later level 1 cache, it was not split into L1d (for data) and L1i (for instructions).
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] Split L1 cache started in 1976 with the IBM 801 CPU, became mainstream in the late 1980s, and in 1997 entered the embedded CPU market with the ARMv5TE.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] As of 2015, even sub-dollar SoCs split the L1 cache.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] They also have L2 caches and, for larger processors, L3 caches as well.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] The L2 cache is usually not split, and acts as a common repository for the already split L1 cache.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] Every core of a multi-core processor has a dedicated L1 cache and is usually not shared between the cores.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] The L2 cache, and lower-level caches, may be shared between the cores.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] L4 cache is currently uncommon, and is generally dynamic random-access memory (DRAM) on a separate die or chip, rather than static random-access memory (SRAM).
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] An exception to this is when eDRAM is used for all levels of cache, down to L1.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] Historically L1 was also on a separate die, however bigger die sizes have allowed integration of it as well as other cache levels, with the possible exception of the last level.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] Each extra level of cache tends to be smaller and faster than the lower levels.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] Caches (like for RAM historically) have generally been sized in powers of: 2, 4, 8, 16 etc.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] KiB; when up to MiB sizes (i.e. for larger non-L1), very early on the pattern broke down, to allow for larger caches without being forced into the doubling-in-size paradigm, with e.g.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] Intel Core 2 Duo with 3 MiB L2 cache in April 2008.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] This happened much later for L1 caches, as their size is generally still a small number of KiB.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] In 2020, some Intel Atom CPUs (with up to 24 cores) have (multiple of) 4.5 MiB and 15 MiB cache sizes.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] Data is transferred between memory and cache in blocks of fixed size, called *cache lines* or *cache blocks*.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] When a cache line is copied from memory into the cache, a cache entry is created.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] The cache entry will include the copied data as well as the requested memory location (called a tag).
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] When the processor needs to read or write a location in memory, it first checks for a corresponding entry in the cache.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] The cache checks for the contents of the requested memory location in any cache lines that might contain that address.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] If the processor finds that the memory location is in the cache, a **cache hit** has occurred.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] However, if the processor does not find the memory location in the cache, a **cache miss** has occurred.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] In the case of a cache hit, the processor immediately reads or writes the data in the cache line.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] For a cache miss, the cache allocates a new entry and copies data from main memory, then the request is fulfilled from the contents of the cache.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] To make room for the new entry on a cache miss, the cache may have to evict one of the existing entries.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] The heuristic it uses to choose the entry to evict is called the replacement policy.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] The fundamental problem with any replacement policy is that it must predict which existing cache entry is least likely to be used in the future.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] Predicting the future is generally difficult, so there is no perfect method to choose among the variety of replacement policies available.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] One popular replacement policy, least-recently used (LRU), replaces the least recently accessed entry.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] Marking some memory ranges as non-cacheable can improve performance, by avoiding caching of memory regions that are rarely re-accessed.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] This avoids the overhead of loading something into the cache without having any reuse.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] Cache entries may also be disabled or locked depending on the context.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] If data are written to the cache, at some point they must also be written to main memory; the timing of this write is known as the write policy.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] In a write-through cache, every write to the cache causes a write to main memory.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] Alternatively, in a write-back or copy-back cache, writes are not immediately mirrored to the main memory, with locations been written over being marked as dirty, being written back to the main memory only when they are evicted from the cache.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] For this reason, a read miss in a write-back cache may sometimes require two memory accesses to service: one to first write the dirty location to main memory, and then another to read the new location from memory.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] Also, a write to a main memory location that is not yet mapped in a write-back cache may evict an already dirty location, thereby freeing that cache space for the new memory location.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] There are intermediate policies as well.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] The cache may be write-through, but the writes may be held in a store data queue temporarily, usually so multiple stores can be processed together (which can reduce bus turnarounds and improve bus utilization).
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] Cached data from the main memory may be changed by other entities (e.g., peripherals using direct memory access (DMA) or another core in a multi-core processor), in which case the copy in the cache may become out-of-date or stale.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] Alternatively, when a CPU in a multiprocessor system updates data in the cache, copies of data in caches associated with other CPUs become stale.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] Communication protocols between the cache managers that keep the data consistent are known as cache coherence protocols.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] Cache performance measurement has become important in recent times where the speed gap between the memory performance and the processor performance is increasing exponentially.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] The cache was introduced to reduce this speed gap.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] Thus knowing how well the cache is able to bridge the gap in the speed of processor and memory becomes important, especially in high-performance systems.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] The cache hit rate and the cache miss rate play an important role in determining this performance.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] To improve the cache performance, reducing the miss rate becomes one of the necessary steps among other steps.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] Decreasing the access time to the cache also gives a boost to its performance and helps with optimization.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] The time taken to fetch one cache line from memory (read latency due to a cache miss) matters because the CPU will run out of work while waiting for the cache line.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] When a CPU reaches this state, it is called a stall.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] As CPUs become faster compared to main memory, stalls due to cache misses displace more potential computation; modern CPUs can execute hundreds of instructions in the time taken to fetch a single cache line from main memory.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] Various techniques have been employed to keep the CPU busy during this time, including out-of-order execution in which the CPU attempts to execute independent instructions after the instruction that is waiting for the cache miss data.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] Another technology, used by many processors, is simultaneous multithreading (SMT), which allows an alternate thread to use the CPU core while the first thread waits for required CPU resources to become available.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] The placement policy decides where in the cache a copy of a particular entry of main memory will go.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] If the placement policy is free to choose any entry in the cache to hold the copy, the cache is called *fully associative*.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] At the other extreme, if each entry in the main memory can go in just one place in the cache, the cache is *direct-mapped*.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] Many caches implement a compromise in which each entry in the main memory can go to any one of N places in the cache, and are described as N-way set associative.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] For example, the level-1 data cache in an AMD Athlon is two-way set associative, which means that any particular location in main memory can be cached in either of two locations in the level-1 data cache.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] Choosing the right value of associativity involves a trade-off.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] If there are ten places to which the placement policy could have mapped a memory location, then to check if that location is in the cache, ten cache entries must be searched.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] Checking more places takes more power and chip area, and potentially more time.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] On the other hand, caches with more associativity suffer fewer misses (see conflict misses), so that the CPU wastes less time reading from the slow main memory.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] The general guideline is that doubling the associativity, from direct mapped to two-way, or from two-way to four-way, has about the same effect on raising the hit rate as doubling the cache size.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] However, increasing associativity more than four does not improve hit rate as much, and are generally done for other reasons (see virtual aliasing).
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] Some CPUs can dynamically reduce the associativity of their caches in low-power states, which acts as a power-saving measure.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] In this cache organization, each location in the main memory can go in only one entry in the cache.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] Therefore, a direct-mapped cache can also be called a "one-way set associative" cache.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] It does not have a placement policy as such, since there is no choice of which cache entry's contents to evict.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] This means that if two locations map to the same entry, they may continually knock each other out.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] Although simpler, a direct-mapped cache needs to be much larger than an associative one to give comparable performance, and it is more unpredictable.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] Let x be block number in cache, y be block number of memory, and n be number of blocks in cache, then mapping is done with the help of the equation *x* = *y* mod *n*.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] One benefit of this scheme is that the tags stored in the cache do not have to include that part of the main memory address which is implied by the cache memory's index.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] Since the cache tags have fewer bits, they require fewer transistors, take less space on the processor circuit board or on the microprocessor chip, and can be read and compared faster.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] Also LRU algorithm is especially simple since only one bit needs to be stored for each pair.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] One of the advantages of a direct-mapped cache is that it allows simple and fast speculation.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] Once the address has been computed, the one cache index which might have a copy of that location in memory is known.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] That cache entry can be read, and the processor can continue to work with that data before it finishes checking that the tag actually matches the requested address.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] The idea of having the processor use the cached data before the tag match completes can be applied to associative caches as well.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] A subset of the tag, called a *hint*, can be used to pick just one of the possible cache entries mapping to the requested address.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] The entry selected by the hint can then be used in parallel with checking the full tag.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] The hint technique works best when used in the context of address translation, as explained below.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] Other schemes have been suggested, such as the *skewed cache*, where the index for way 0 is direct, as above, but the index for way 1 is formed with a hash function.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] A good hash function has the property that addresses which conflict with the direct mapping tend not to conflict when mapped with the hash function, and so it is less likely that a program will suffer from an unexpectedly large number of conflict misses due to a pathological access pattern.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] The downside is extra latency from computing the hash function.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] Additionally, when it comes time to load a new line and evict an old line, it may be difficult to determine which existing line was least recently used, because the new line conflicts with data at different indexes in each way; LRU tracking for non-skewed caches is usually done on a per-set basis.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] Nevertheless, skewed-associative caches have major advantages over conventional set-associative ones.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] A true set-associative cache tests all the possible ways simultaneously, using something like a content-addressable memory.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] A pseudo-associative cache tests each possible way one at a time.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] A hash-rehash cache and a column-associative cache are examples of a pseudo-associative cache.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] In the common case of finding a hit in the first way tested, a pseudo-associative cache is as fast as a direct-mapped cache, but it has a much lower conflict miss rate than a direct-mapped cache, closer to the miss rate of a fully associative cache.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] Comparing with a direct-mapped cache, a set associative cache has a reduced number of bits for its cache set index that maps to a cache set, where multiple ways or blocks stays, such as 2 blocks for a 2-way set associative cache and 4 blocks for a 4-way set associative cache.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] Comparing with a direct mapped cache, the unused cache index bits become a part of the tag bits.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] For example, a 2-way set associative cache contributes 1 bit to the tag and a 4-way set associative cache contributes 2 bits to the tag.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] The basic idea of the multicolumn cache is to use the set index to map to a cache set as a conventional set associative cache does, and to use the added tag bits to index a way in the set.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] For example, in a 4-way set associative cache, the two bits are used to index way 00, way 01, way 10, and way 11, respectively.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] This double cache indexing is called a "major location mapping", and its latency is equivalent to a direct-mapped access.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] Extensive experiments in multicolumn cache design shows that the hit ratio to major locations is as high as 90%.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] If cache mapping conflicts with a cache block in the major location, the existing cache block will be moved to another cache way in the same set, which is called "selected location".
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] Because the newly indexed cache block is a most recently used (MRU) block, it is placed in the major location in multicolumn cache with a consideration of temporal locality.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] Since multicolumn cache is designed for a cache with a high associativity, the number of ways in each set is high; thus, it is easy find a selected location in the set.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] A selected location index by an additional hardware is maintained for the major location in a cache block.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] Multicolumn cache remains a high hit ratio due to its high associativity, and has a comparable low latency to a direct-mapped cache due to its high percentage of hits in major locations.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] The *data block* (cache line) contains the actual data fetched from the main memory.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] The *tag* contains (part of) the address of the actual data fetched from the main memory.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] The "size" of the cache is the amount of main memory data it can hold.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] This size can be calculated as the number of bytes stored in each data block times the number of blocks stored in the cache.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] An effective memory address which goes along with the cache line (memory block) is split (MSB to LSB) into the tag, the index and the block offset.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] The index describes which cache set that the data has been put in.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] The index length is $\lceil \log _{2}(s)\rceil$ bits for s cache sets.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] The block offset specifies the desired data within the stored data block within the cache row.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] Typically the effective address is in bytes, so the block offset length is $\lceil \log _{2}(b)\rceil$ bits, where b is the number of bytes per data block.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] The tag contains the most significant bits of the address, which are checked against all rows in the current set (the set has been retrieved by index) to see if this set contains the requested address.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] Some authors refer to the block offset as simply the "offset" or the "displacement".
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] The original Pentium 4 processor had a four-way set associative L1 data cache of 8 KiB in size, with 64-byte cache blocks.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] Hence, there are 8 KiB / 64 = 128 cache blocks.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] The number of sets is equal to the number of cache blocks divided by the number of ways of associativity, what leads to 128 / 4 = 32 sets, and hence 25 = 32 different indices.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] Since the CPU address is 32 bits wide, this implies 32 − 5 − 6 = 21 bits for the tag field.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] The original Pentium 4 processor also had an eight-way set associative L2 integrated cache 256 KiB in size, with 128-byte cache blocks.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] This implies 32 − 8 − 7 = 17 bits for the tag field.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] An instruction cache requires only one flag bit per cache row entry: a valid bit.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] The valid bit indicates whether or not a cache block has been loaded with valid data.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] On power-up, the hardware sets all the valid bits in all the caches to "invalid".
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] Some systems also set a valid bit to "invalid" at other times, such as when multi-master bus snooping hardware in the cache of one processor hears an address broadcast from some other processor, and realizes that certain data blocks in the local cache are now stale and should be marked invalid.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] A data cache typically requires two flag bits per cache line – a valid bit and a dirty bit.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] Having a dirty bit set indicates that the associated cache line has been changed since it was read from main memory ("dirty"), meaning that the processor has written data to that line and the new value has not propagated all the way to main memory.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] A cache miss is a failed attempt to read or write a piece of data in the cache, which results in a main memory access with much longer latency.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] There are three kinds of cache misses: instruction read miss, data read miss, and data write miss.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] Most general purpose CPUs implement some form of virtual memory.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] To summarize, either each program running on the machine sees its own simplified address space, which contains code and data for that program only, or all programs run in a common virtual address space.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] A program executes by calculating, comparing, reading and writing to addresses of its virtual address space, rather than addresses of physical address space, making programs simpler and thus easier to write.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] Virtual memory requires the processor to translate virtual addresses generated by the program into physical addresses in main memory.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] The portion of the processor that does this translation is known as the memory management unit (MMU).
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] The fast path through the MMU can perform those translations stored in the translation lookaside buffer (TLB), which is a cache of mappings from the operating system's page table, segment table, or both.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] One early virtual memory system, the IBM M44/44X, required an access to a mapping table held in core memory before every programmed access to main memory.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] With no caches, and with the mapping table memory running at the same speed as main memory this effectively cut the speed of memory access in half.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] Two early machines that used a page table in main memory for mapping, the IBM System/360 Model 67 and the GE 645, both had a small associative memory as a cache for accesses to the in-memory page table.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] Both machines predated the first machine with a cache for main memory, the IBM System/360 Model 85, so the first hardware cache used in a computer system was not a data or instruction cache, but rather a TLB.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] The speed of this recurrence (the *load latency*) is crucial to CPU performance, and so most modern level-1 caches are virtually indexed, which at least allows the MMU's TLB lookup to proceed in parallel with fetching the data from the cache RAM.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] But virtual indexing is not the best choice for all cache levels.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] The cost of dealing with virtual aliases grows with cache size, and as a result most level-2 and larger caches are physically indexed.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] Caches have historically used both virtual and physical addresses for the cache tags, although virtual tagging is now uncommon.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] If the TLB lookup can finish before the cache RAM lookup, then the physical address is available in time for tag compare, and there is no need for virtual tagging.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] Large caches, then, tend to be physically tagged, and only small, very low latency caches are virtually tagged.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] In recent general-purpose CPUs, virtual tagging has been superseded by virtual hints, as described below.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] A cache that relies on virtual indexing and tagging becomes inconsistent after the same virtual address is mapped into different physical addresses (homonym), which can be solved by using physical address for tagging, or by storing the address space identifier in the cache line.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] However, the latter approach does not help against the synonym problem, in which several cache lines end up storing data for the same physical address.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] Writing to such locations may update only one location in the cache, leaving the others with inconsistent data.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] This issue may be solved by using non-overlapping memory layouts for different address spaces, or otherwise the cache (or a part of it) must be flushed when the mapping changes.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] The great advantage of virtual tags is that, for associative caches, they allow the tag match to proceed before the virtual to physical translation is done.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] However, coherence probes and evictions present a physical address for action.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] The hardware must have some means of converting the physical addresses into a cache index, generally by storing physical tags as well as virtual tags.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] For comparison, a physically tagged cache does not need to keep virtual tags, which is simpler.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] When a virtual to physical mapping is deleted from the TLB, cache entries with those virtual addresses will have to be flushed somehow.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] Alternatively, if cache entries are allowed on pages not mapped by the TLB, then those entries will have to be flushed when the access rights on those pages are changed in the page table.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] It is also possible for the operating system to ensure that no virtual aliases are simultaneously resident in the cache.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] The operating system makes this guarantee by enforcing page coloring, which is described below.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] Some early RISC processors (SPARC, RS/6000) took this approach.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] It has not been used recently, as the hardware cost of detecting and evicting virtual aliases has fallen and the software complexity and performance penalty of perfect page coloring has risen.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] It can be useful to distinguish the two functions of tags in an associative cache: they are used to determine which way of the entry set to select, and they are used to determine if the cache hit or missed.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] The second function must always be correct, but it is permissible for the first function to guess, and get the wrong answer occasionally.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] Some processors (e.g. early SPARCs) have caches with both virtual and physical tags.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] The virtual tags are used for way selection, and the physical tags are used for determining hit or miss.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] This kind of cache enjoys the latency advantage of a virtually tagged cache, and the simple software interface of a physically tagged cache.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] It bears the added cost of duplicated tags, however.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] Also, during miss processing, the alternate ways of the cache line indexed have to be probed for virtual aliases and any matches evicted.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] The extra area (and some latency) can be mitigated by keeping *virtual hints* with each cache entry instead of virtual tags.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] These hints are a subset or hash of the virtual tag, and are used for selecting the way of the cache from which to get data and a physical tag.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] Like a virtually tagged cache, there may be a virtual hint match but physical tag mismatch, in which case the cache entry with the matching hint must be evicted so that cache accesses after the cache fill at this address will have just one hint match.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] Since virtual hints have fewer bits than virtual tags distinguishing them from one another, a virtually hinted cache suffers more conflict misses than a virtually tagged cache.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] Perhaps the ultimate reduction of virtual hints can be found in the Pentium 4 (Willamette and Northwood cores).
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] In these processors the virtual hint is effectively two bits, and the cache is four-way set associative.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] Effectively, the hardware maintains a simple permutation from virtual address to cache index, so that no content-addressable memory (CAM) is necessary to select the right one of the four ways fetched.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] Large physically indexed caches (usually secondary caches) run into a problem: the operating system rather than the application controls which pages collide with one another in the cache.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] Differences in page allocation from one program run to the next lead to differences in the cache collision patterns, which can lead to very large differences in program performance.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] These differences can make it very difficult to get a consistent and repeatable timing for a benchmark run.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] To understand the problem, consider a CPU with a 1 MiB physically indexed direct-mapped level-2 cache and 4 KiB virtual memory pages.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] Sequential physical pages map to sequential locations in the cache until after 256 pages the pattern wraps around.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] We can label each physical page with a color of 0–255 to denote where in the cache it can go.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] Locations within physical pages with different colors cannot conflict in the cache.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] Programmers attempting to make maximum use of the cache may arrange their programs' access patterns so that only 1 MiB of data need be cached at any given time, thus avoiding capacity misses.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] But they should also ensure that the access patterns do not have conflict misses.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] One way to think about this problem is to divide up the virtual pages the program uses and assign them virtual colors in the same way as physical colors were assigned to physical pages before.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] Programmers can then arrange the access patterns of their code so that no two pages with the same virtual color are in use at the same time.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] There is a wide literature on such optimizations (e.g. loop nest optimization), largely coming from the High Performance Computing (HPC) community.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] The snag is that while all the pages in use at any given moment may have different virtual colors, some may have the same physical colors.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] In fact, if the operating system assigns physical pages to virtual pages randomly and uniformly, it is extremely likely that some pages will have the same physical color, and then locations from those pages will collide in the cache (this is the birthday paradox).
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] The solution is to have the operating system attempt to assign different physical color pages to different virtual colors, a technique called *page coloring*.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] Although the actual mapping from virtual to physical color is irrelevant to system performance, odd mappings are difficult to keep track of and have little benefit, so most approaches to page coloring simply try to keep physical and virtual page colors the same.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] If the operating system can guarantee that each physical page maps to only one virtual color, then there are no virtual aliases, and the processor can use virtually indexed caches with no need for extra virtual alias probes during miss handling.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] Alternatively, the OS can flush a page from the cache whenever it changes from one virtual color to another.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] As mentioned above, this approach was used for some early SPARC and RS/6000 designs.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] The software page coloring technique has been used to effectively partition the shared Last level Cache (LLC) in multicore processors.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p01] This operating system-based LLC management in multicore processors has been adopted by Intel.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] Modern processors have multiple interacting on-chip caches.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] The operation of a particular cache can be completely specified by the cache size, the cache block size, the number of blocks in a set, the cache set replacement policy, and the cache write policy (write-through or write-back).
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] While all of the cache blocks in a particular cache are the same size and have the same associativity, typically the "higher-level" caches (called Level 1 cache) have a smaller number of blocks, smaller block size, and fewer blocks in a set, but have very short access times.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] Level 2 and below) have progressively larger numbers of blocks, larger block size, more blocks in a set, and relatively longer access times, but are still much faster than main memory.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] Cache entry replacement policy is determined by a cache algorithm selected to be implemented by the processor designers.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] In some cases, multiple algorithms are provided for different kinds of work loads.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] Pipelined CPUs access memory from multiple points in the pipeline: instruction fetch, virtual-to-physical address translation, and data fetch (see classic RISC pipeline).
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] The natural design is to use different physical caches for each of these points, so that no one physical resource has to be scheduled to service two points in the pipeline.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] Thus the pipeline naturally ends up with at least three separate caches (instruction, TLB, and data), each specialized to its particular role.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] A **victim cache** is a cache used to hold blocks evicted from a CPU cache upon replacement.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] The victim cache lies between the main cache and its refill path, and holds only those blocks of data that were evicted from the main cache.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] The victim cache is usually fully associative, and is intended to reduce the number of conflict misses.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] Many commonly used programs do not require an associative mapping for all the accesses.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] In fact, only a small fraction of the memory accesses of the program require high associativity.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] The victim cache exploits this property by providing high associativity to only these accesses.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] It was introduced by Norman Jouppi from DEC in 1990.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] Intel's *Crystalwell* variant of its Haswell processors introduced an on-package 128 MiB eDRAM Level 4 cache which serves as a victim cache to the processors' Level 3 cache.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] In the Skylake microarchitecture the Level 4 cache no longer works as a victim cache.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] One of the more extreme examples of cache specialization is the **trace cache** (also known as *execution trace cache*) found in the Intel Pentium 4 microprocessors.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] A trace cache is a mechanism for increasing the instruction fetch bandwidth and decreasing power consumption (in the case of the Pentium 4) by storing traces of instructions that have already been fetched and decoded.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] A trace cache stores instructions either after they have been decoded, or as they are retired.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] Generally, instructions are added to trace caches in groups representing either individual basic blocks or dynamic instruction traces.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] The Pentium 4's trace cache stores micro-operations resulting from decoding x86 instructions, providing also the functionality of a micro-operation cache.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] Having this, the next time an instruction is needed, it does not have to be decoded into micro-ops again.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] Write Coalescing Cache is a special cache that is part of L2 cache in AMD's Bulldozer microarchitecture.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] Stores from both L1D caches in the module go through the WCC, where they are buffered and coalesced.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] The WCC's task is reducing number of writes to the L2 cache.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] A **micro-operation cache** (**μop cache**, **uop cache** or **UC**) is a specialized cache that stores micro-operations of decoded instructions, as received directly from the instruction decoders or from the instruction cache.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] When an instruction needs to be decoded, the μop cache is checked for its decoded form which is re-used if cached; if it is not available, the instruction is decoded and then cached.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] One of the early works describing μop cache as an alternative frontend for the Intel P6 processor family is the 2001 paper *"Micro-Operation Cache: A Power Aware Frontend for Variable Instruction Length ISA"*.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] Later, Intel included μop caches in its Sandy Bridge processors and in successive microarchitectures like Ivy Bridge and Haswell.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] AMD implemented a μop cache in their Zen microarchitecture.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] Fetching complete pre-decoded instructions eliminates the need to repeatedly decode variable length complex instructions into simpler fixed-length micro-operations, and simplifies the process of predicting, fetching, rotating and aligning fetched instructions.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] A μop cache effectively offloads the fetch and decode hardware, thus decreasing power consumption and improving the frontend supply of decoded micro-operations.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] The μop cache also increases performance by more consistently delivering decoded micro-operations to the backend and eliminating various bottlenecks in the CPU's fetch and decode logic.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] A μop cache has many similarities with a trace cache, although a μop cache is much simpler thus providing better power efficiency; this makes it better suited for implementations on battery-powered devices.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] The main disadvantage of the trace cache, leading to its power inefficiency, is the hardware complexity required for its heuristic deciding on caching and reusing dynamically created instruction traces.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] A **branch target cache** or **branch target instruction cache**, the name used on ARM microprocessors, is a specialized cache which holds the first few instructions at the destination of a taken branch.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] This is used by low-powered processors which do not need a normal instruction cache because the memory system is capable of delivering instructions fast enough to satisfy the CPU without one.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] However, this only applies to consecutive instructions in sequence; it still takes several cycles of latency to restart instruction fetch at a new address, causing a few cycles of pipeline bubble after a control transfer.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] A branch target cache provides instructions for those few cycles avoiding a delay after most taken branches.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] This allows full-speed operation with a much smaller cache than a traditional full-time instruction cache.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] Smart Cache shares the actual cache memory between the cores of a multi-core processor.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] In comparison to a dedicated per-core cache, the overall cache miss rate decreases when cores do not require equal parts of the cache space.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] Consequently, a single core can use the full level 2 or level 3 cache while the other cores are inactive.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] Furthermore, the shared cache makes it faster to share memory among different execution cores.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] Another issue is the fundamental tradeoff between cache latency and hit rate.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] Larger caches have better hit rates but longer latency.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] To address this tradeoff, many computers use multiple levels of cache, with small fast caches backed up by larger, slower caches.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] Multi-level caches generally operate by checking the fastest but smallest cache, *level 1* (**L1**), first; if it hits, the processor proceeds at high speed.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] If that cache misses, the slower but larger next level cache, *level 2* (**L2**), is checked, and so on, before accessing external memory.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] As the latency difference between main memory and the fastest cache has become larger, some processors have begun to utilize as many as three levels of on-chip cache.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] Price-sensitive designs used this to pull the entire cache hierarchy on-chip, but by the 2010s some of the highest-performance designs returned to having large off-chip caches, which is often implemented in eDRAM and mounted on a multi-chip module, as a fourth cache level.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] In rare cases, such as in the mainframe CPU IBM z15 (2019), all levels down to L1 are implemented by eDRAM, replacing SRAM entirely (for cache, SRAM is still used for registers).
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] Apple's ARM-based Apple silicon series, starting with the A14 and M1, have a 192 KiB L1i cache for each of the high-performance cores, an unusually large amount; however the high-efficiency cores only have 128 KiB.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] Since then other processors such as Intel's Lunar Lake and Qualcomm's Oryon have also implemented similar L1i cache sizes.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] The benefits of L3 and L4 caches depend on the application's access patterns.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] However, with register renaming most compiler register assignments are reallocated dynamically by hardware at runtime into a register bank, allowing the CPU to break false data dependencies and thus easing pipeline hazards.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] Register files sometimes also have hierarchy: The Cray-1 (circa 1976) had eight address "A" and eight scalar data "S" registers that were generally usable.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] There was also a set of 64 address "B" and 64 scalar data "T" registers that took longer to access, but were faster than main memory.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] The "B" and "T" registers were provided because the Cray-1 did not have a data cache.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] When considering a chip with multiple cores, there is a question of whether the caches should be shared or local to each core.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] Implementing shared cache inevitably introduces more wiring and complexity.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] But then, having one cache per *chip*, rather than *core*, greatly reduces the amount of space needed, and thus one can include a larger cache.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] Typically, sharing the L1 cache is undesirable because the resulting increase in latency would make each core run considerably slower than a single-core chip.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] For example, an eight-core chip with three levels may include an L1 cache for each core, one intermediate L2 cache for each pair of cores, and one L3 cache shared between all cores.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] A shared highest-level cache (usually L3, called before accessing memory), is usually referred to as a *last-level cache* (LLC).
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] Additional techniques are used for increasing the level of parallelism when LLC is shared between multiple cores, including slicing it into multiple pieces which are addressing certain ranges of memory addresses, and can be accessed independently.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] In a separate cache structure, instructions and data are cached separately, meaning that a cache line is used to cache either instructions or data, but not both; various benefits have been demonstrated with separate data and instruction translation lookaside buffers.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] In a unified structure, this constraint is not present, and cache lines can be used to cache both instructions and data.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] Multi-level caches introduce new design decisions.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] For instance, in some processors, all data in the L1 cache must also be somewhere in the L2 cache.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] These caches are called *strictly inclusive*.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] Other processors (like the AMD Athlon) have *exclusive* caches: data are guaranteed to be in at most one of the L1 and L2 caches, never in both.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] Still other processors (like the Intel Pentium II, III, and 4) do not require that data in the L1 cache also reside in the L2 cache, although it may often do so.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] There is no universally accepted name for this intermediate policy; two common names are "non-exclusive" and "partially-inclusive".
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] The advantage of exclusive caches is that they store more data.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] This advantage is larger when the exclusive L1 cache is comparable to the L2 cache, and diminishes if the L2 cache is many times larger than the L1 cache.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] When the L1 misses and the L2 hits on an access, the hitting cache line in the L2 is exchanged with a line in the L1.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] This exchange is quite a bit more work than just copying a line from L2 to L1, which is what an inclusive cache does.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] One advantage of strictly inclusive caches is that when external devices or other processors in a multiprocessor system wish to remove a cache line from the processor, they need only have the processor check the L2 cache.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] In cache hierarchies which do not enforce inclusion, the L1 cache must be checked as well.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] As a drawback, there is a correlation between the associativities of L1 and L2 caches: if the L2 cache does not have at least as many ways as all L1 caches together, the effective associativity of the L1 caches is restricted.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] Another disadvantage of inclusive cache is that whenever there is an eviction in L2 cache, the (possibly) corresponding lines in L1 also have to get evicted in order to maintain inclusiveness.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] This is quite a bit of work, and would result in a higher L1 miss rate.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] Another advantage of inclusive caches is that the larger cache can use larger cache lines, which reduces the size of the secondary cache tags.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] Scratchpad memory (SPM), also known as scratchpad, scratchpad RAM or local store in computer terminology, is a high-speed internal memory used for temporary storage of calculations, data, and other work in progress.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] To illustrate both specialization and multi-level caching, here is the cache hierarchy of the K8 core in the AMD Athlon 64 CPU.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] The K8 has four specialized caches: an instruction cache, an instruction TLB, a data TLB, and a data cache.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] There are second-level instruction and data TLBs, which store only PTEs mapping 4 KiB.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] Both instruction and data caches, and the various TLBs, can fill from the large **unified** L2 cache.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] This cache is exclusive to both the L1 instruction and data caches, which means that any 8-byte line can only be in one of the L1 instruction cache, the L1 data cache, or the L2 cache.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] It is, however, possible for a line in the data cache to have a PTE which is also in one of the TLBs—the operating system is responsible for keeping the TLBs coherent by flushing portions of them when the page tables in memory are updated.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] The K8 also caches information that is never stored in memory—prediction information.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] These caches are not shown in the above diagram.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] As is usual for this class of CPU, the K8 has fairly complex branch prediction, with tables that help predict whether branches are taken and other tables which predict the targets of branches and jumps.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] Some of this information is associated with instructions, in both the level 1 instruction cache and the unified secondary cache.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] The K8 uses an interesting trick to store prediction information with instructions in the secondary cache.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] Lines in the secondary cache are protected from accidental data corruption (e.g. by an alpha particle strike) by either ECC or parity, depending on whether those lines were evicted from the data or instruction primary caches.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] Since the parity code takes fewer bits than the ECC code, lines from the instruction cache have a few spare bits.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] These bits are used to cache branch prediction information associated with those instructions.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] The net result is that the branch predictor has a larger effective history table, and so has better accuracy.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] Other processors have other kinds of predictors (e.g., the store-to-load bypass predictor in the DEC Alpha 21264).
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] These predictors are caches in that they store information that is costly to compute.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] Some of the terminology used when discussing predictors is the same as that for caches (one speaks of a **hit** in a branch predictor), but predictors are not generally thought of as part of the cache hierarchy.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] The K8 keeps the instruction and data caches **coherent** in hardware, which means that a store into an instruction closely following the store instruction will change that following instruction.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] Other processors, like those in the Alpha and MIPS family, have relied on software to keep the instruction cache coherent.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] Stores are not guaranteed to show up in the instruction stream until a program calls an operating system facility to ensure coherency.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] In computer engineering, a *tag RAM* is used to specify which of the possible memory locations is currently stored in a CPU cache.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] For a simple, direct-mapped design fast SRAM can be used.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] Higher associative caches usually employ content-addressable memory.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] Cache **reads** are the most common CPU operation that takes more than a single cycle.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] Program execution time tends to be very sensitive to the latency of a level-1 data cache hit.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] A great deal of design effort, and often power and silicon area are expended making the caches as fast as possible.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] The simplest cache is a virtually indexed direct-mapped cache.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] The virtual address is calculated with an adder, the relevant portion of the address extracted and used to index an SRAM, which returns the loaded data.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] The data are byte aligned in a byte shifter, and from there are bypassed to the next operation.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] There is no need for any tag checking in the inner loop – in fact, the tags need not even be read.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] Later in the pipeline, but before the load instruction is retired, the tag for the loaded data must be read, and checked against the virtual address to make sure there was a cache hit.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] On a miss, the cache is updated with the requested cache line and the pipeline is restarted.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] An associative cache is more complicated, because some form of tag must be read to determine which entry of the cache to select.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] An N-way set-associative level-1 cache usually reads all N possible tags and N data in parallel, and then chooses the data associated with the matching tag.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] Level-2 caches sometimes save power by reading the tags first, so that only one data element is read from the data SRAM.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] The adjacent diagram is intended to clarify the manner in which the various fields of the address are used.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] Address bit 31 is most significant, bit 0 is least significant.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] The diagram shows the SRAMs, indexing, and multiplexing for a 4 KiB, 2-way set-associative, virtually indexed and virtually tagged cache with 64 byte (B) lines, a 32-bit read width and 32-bit virtual address.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] Because the cache is 4 KiB and has 64 B lines, there are just 64 lines in the cache, and we read two at a time from a Tag SRAM which has 32 rows, each with a pair of 21 bit tags.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] Although any function of virtual address bits 31 through 6 could be used to index the tag and data SRAMs, it is simplest to use the least significant bits.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] Similarly, because the cache is 4 KiB and has a 4 B read path, and reads two ways for each access, the Data SRAM is 512 rows by 8 bytes wide.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] A more modern cache might be 16 KiB, 4-way set-associative, virtually indexed, virtually hinted, and physically tagged, with 32 B lines, 32-bit read width and 36-bit physical addresses.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] The read path recurrence for such a cache looks very similar to the path above.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] Instead of tags, virtual hints are read, and matched against a subset of the virtual address.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] Later on in the pipeline, the virtual address is translated into a physical address by the TLB, and the physical tag is read (just one, as the virtual hint supplies which way of the cache to read).
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] Finally the physical address is compared to the physical tag to determine if a hit has occurred.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] Some SPARC designs have improved the speed of their L1 caches by a few gate delays by collapsing the virtual address adder into the SRAM decoders.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] The early history of cache technology is closely tied to the invention and use of virtual memory.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] Because of scarcity and cost of semi-conductor memories, early mainframe computers in the 1960s used a complex hierarchy of physical memory, mapped onto a flat virtual memory space used by programs.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] The memory technologies would span semi-conductor, magnetic core, drum and disc.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] Virtual memory seen and used by programs would be flat and caching would be used to fetch data and instructions into the fastest memory ahead of processor access.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] Extensive studies were done to optimize the cache sizes.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] Optimal values were found to depend greatly on the programming language used with Algol needing the smallest and Fortran and Cobol needing the largest cache sizes.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] In the early days of microcomputer technology, memory access was only slightly slower than register access.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] But since the 1980s the performance gap between processor and memory has been growing.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] Microprocessors have advanced much faster than memory, especially in terms of their operating frequency, so memory became a performance bottleneck.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] While it was technically possible to have all the main memory as fast as the CPU, a more economically viable path has been taken: use plenty of low-speed memory, but also introduce a small high-speed cache memory to alleviate the performance gap.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] This provided an order of magnitude more capacity—for the same price—with only a slightly reduced combined performance.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] The first documented uses of a TLB were on the GE 645 and the IBM 360/67, both of which used an associative memory as a TLB.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] The first documented use of an instruction cache was on the CDC 6600.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] The first documented use of a data cache was on the IBM System/360 Model 85.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] The 68010, released in 1982, has a "loop mode" which can be considered a tiny and special-case instruction cache that accelerates loops that consist of only two instructions.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] The 68020, released in 1984, replaced that with a typical instruction cache of 256 bytes, being the first 68k series processor to feature true on-chip cache memory.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] The 68030, released in 1987, is basically a 68020 core with an additional 256-byte data cache, an on-chip memory management unit (MMU), a process shrink, and added burst mode for the caches.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] The 68040, released in 1990, has split instruction and data caches of four kilobytes each.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] The 68060, released in 1994, has the following: 8 KiB data cache (four-way associative), 8 KiB instruction cache (four-way associative), 96-byte FIFO instruction buffer, 256-entry branch cache, and 64-entry address translation cache MMU buffer (four-way associative).
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] As the x86 microprocessors reached clock rates of 20 MHz and above in the 386, small amounts of fast cache memory began to be featured in systems to improve performance.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] This was because the DRAM used for main memory had significant latency, up to 120 ns, as well as refresh cycles.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] The cache was constructed from more expensive, but significantly faster, SRAM memory cells, which at the time had latencies around 10–25 ns.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] The early caches were external to the processor and typically located on the motherboard in the form of eight or nine DIP devices placed in sockets to enable the cache as an optional extra or upgrade feature.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] Some versions of the Intel 386 processor could support 16 to 256 KiB of external cache.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] With the 486 processor, an 8 KiB cache was integrated directly into the CPU die.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] This cache was termed Level 1 or L1 cache to differentiate it from the slower on-motherboard, or Level 2 (L2) cache.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] These on-motherboard caches were much larger, with the most common size being 256 KiB.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] There were some system boards that contained sockets for the Intel 485Turbocache daughtercard which had either 64 or 128 Kbyte of cache memory.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] The popularity of on-motherboard cache continued through the Pentium MMX era but was made obsolete by the introduction of SDRAM and the growing disparity between bus clock rates and CPU clock rates, which caused on-motherboard cache to be only slightly faster than main memory.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] The next development in cache implementation in the x86 microprocessors began with the Pentium Pro, which brought the secondary cache onto the same package as the microprocessor, clocked at the same frequency as the microprocessor.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] On-motherboard caches enjoyed prolonged popularity thanks to the AMD K6-2 and AMD K6-III processors that still used Socket 7, which was previously used by Intel with on-motherboard caches.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] K6-III included 256 KiB on-die L2 cache and took advantage of the on-board cache as a third level cache, named L3 (motherboards with up to 2 MiB of on-board cache were produced).
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] After the Socket 7 became obsolete, on-motherboard cache disappeared from the x86 systems.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] The three-level caches were used again first with the introduction of the Intel Xeon MP "Foster Core", where the L3 cache was added to the CPU die.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] It became common for the total cache sizes to be increasingly larger in newer processor generations, and recently (as of 2011) it is not uncommon to find Level 3 cache sizes of tens of megabytes.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] Intel introduced a Level 4 on-package cache with the Haswell microarchitecture.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] *Crystalwell* Haswell CPUs, equipped with the GT3e variant of Intel's integrated Iris Pro graphics, effectively feature 128 MiB of embedded DRAM (eDRAM) on the same package.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] This L4 cache is shared dynamically between the on-die GPU and CPU, and serves as a victim cache to the CPU's L3 cache.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] The Apple M1 CPU has 128 or 192 KiB of L1 instruction cache for each core (important for latency/single-thread performance), depending on core type.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] This is an unusually large L1 cache for any CPU type (not just for a laptop); the total cache memory size is not unusually large (the total is more important for throughput) for a laptop, and much larger total (e.g.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] L3 or L4) sizes are available in IBM's mainframes.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] Early cache designs focused entirely on the direct cost of cache and RAM and average execution speed.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] More recent cache designs also consider energy efficiency, fault tolerance, and other goals.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] There are several tools available to computer architects to help explore tradeoffs between the cache cycle time, energy, and area; the CACTI cache simulator and the SimpleScalar instruction set simulator are two open-source options.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] A multi-ported cache is a cache which can serve more than one request at a time.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] When accessing a traditional cache we normally use a single memory address, whereas in a multi-ported cache we may request N addresses at a time – where N is the number of ports that connected through the processor and the cache.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] The benefit of this is that a pipelined processor may access memory from different phases in its pipeline.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/cpu-cache-p02] Another benefit is that it allows the concept of super-scalar processors through different cache levels.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/locality-of-reference] In computer science, **locality of reference**, also known as the **principle of locality**, is the tendency of a processor to access the same set of memory locations repetitively over a short period of time.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/locality-of-reference] There are two basic types of reference locality – temporal and spatial locality.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/locality-of-reference] Temporal locality refers to the reuse of specific data and/or resources within a relatively small time duration.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/locality-of-reference] Spatial locality (also termed *data locality*) refers to the use of data elements within relatively close storage locations.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/locality-of-reference] Sequential locality, a special case of spatial locality, occurs when data elements are arranged and accessed linearly, such as traversing the elements in a one-dimensional array.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/locality-of-reference] Locality is a type of predictable behavior that occurs in computer systems.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/locality-of-reference] Systems which exhibit strong *locality of reference* are good candidates for performance optimization through the use of techniques such as the caching, prefetching for memory and advanced branch predictors of a processor core.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/locality-of-reference] When the matrix size is small, performance differences between traversal methods may appear minimal because the entire dataset fits inside the processor cache.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/locality-of-reference] However, as matrix dimensions increase, the access pattern becomes a critical factor, since non-sequential traversals generate significantly more cache misses and RAM accesses, reducing overall computational efficiency.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/locality-of-reference] In order to benefit from temporal and spatial locality, which occur frequently, most of the information storage systems are hierarchical.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/locality-of-reference] Equidistant locality is usually supported by a processor's diverse nontrivial increment instructions.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/locality-of-reference] For branch locality, contemporary processors have sophisticated branch predictors, and on the basis of this prediction the memory manager of the processor tries to collect and preprocess the data of plausible alternatives.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/locality-of-reference] These reasons are either goals to achieve or circumstances to accept, depending on the aspect.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/locality-of-reference] If most of the time the substantial portion of the references aggregate into clusters, and if the shape of this system of clusters can be well predicted, then it can be used for performance optimization.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/locality-of-reference] There are several ways to benefit from locality using optimization techniques.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/locality-of-reference] Hierarchical memory is a hardware optimization that takes the benefits of spatial and temporal locality and can be used on several levels of the memory hierarchy.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/locality-of-reference] Paging obviously benefits from temporal and spatial locality.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/locality-of-reference] A cache is a simple example of exploiting temporal locality, because it is a specially designed, faster but smaller memory area, generally used to keep recently referenced data and data near recently referenced data, which can lead to potential performance increases.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/locality-of-reference] Data elements in a cache do not necessarily correspond to data elements that are spatially close in the main memory; however, data elements are brought into cache one cache line at a time.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/locality-of-reference] This means that spatial locality is again important: if one element is referenced, a few neighboring elements will also be brought into cache.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/locality-of-reference] Finally, temporal locality plays a role on the lowest level, since results that are referenced very closely together can be kept in the machine registers.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/locality-of-reference] Some programming languages (such as C) allow the programmer to suggest that certain variables be kept in registers.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/locality-of-reference] Data locality is a typical memory reference feature of regular programs (though many irregular memory access patterns exist).
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/locality-of-reference] It makes the hierarchical memory layout profitable.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/locality-of-reference] In computers, memory is divided into a hierarchy in order to speed up data accesses.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/locality-of-reference] The lower levels of the memory hierarchy tend to be slower, but larger.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/locality-of-reference] Thus, a program will achieve greater performance if it uses memory while it is cached in the upper levels of the memory hierarchy and avoids bringing other data into the upper levels of the hierarchy that will displace data that will be used shortly in the future.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/locality-of-reference] This is an ideal, and sometimes cannot be achieved.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/locality-of-reference] Modern machines tend to read blocks of lower memory into the next level of the memory hierarchy.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/locality-of-reference] If this displaces used memory, the operating system tries to predict which data will be accessed least (or latest) and move it down the memory hierarchy.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/locality-of-reference] Prediction algorithms tend to be simple to reduce hardware complexity, though they are becoming somewhat more complicated.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/locality-of-reference] By switching the looping order for `j` and `k`, the speedup in large matrix multiplications becomes dramatic, at least for languages that put contiguous array elements in the last dimension.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/locality-of-reference] This will not change the mathematical result, but it improves efficiency.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/locality-of-reference] In this case, "large" means, approximately, more than 100,000 elements in each matrix, or enough addressable memory such that the matrices will not fit in L1 and L2 caches.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/locality-of-reference] The reason for this speedup is that in the first case, the reads of `A[i][k]` are in cache (since the `k` index is the contiguous, last dimension), but `B[k][j]` is not, so there is a cache miss penalty on `B[k][j]`.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/locality-of-reference] `C[i][j]` is irrelevant, because it can be hoisted out of the inner loop -- the loop variable there is `k`.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/locality-of-reference] In the second case, the reads and writes of `C[i][j]` are both in cache, the reads of `B[k][j]` are in cache, and the read of `A[i][k]` can be hoisted out of the inner loop.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/locality-of-reference] Thus, the second example has no cache miss penalty in the inner loop while the first example has a cache penalty.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/locality-of-reference] On a year 2014 processor, the second case is approximately five times faster than the first case, when written in C and compiled with `gcc -O3`.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/locality-of-reference] Temporal locality can also be improved in the above example by using a technique called blocking.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/locality-of-reference] The larger matrix can be divided into evenly sized sub-matrices, so that the smaller blocks can be referenced (multiplied) several times while in memory.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/locality-of-reference] Note that this example works for square matrices of dimensions SIZE x SIZE, but it can easily be extended for arbitrary matrices by substituting SIZE_I, SIZE_J and SIZE_K where appropriate.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/locality-of-reference] The temporal locality of the above solution is provided because a block can be used several times before moving on, so that it is moved in and out of memory less often.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/locality-of-reference] Spatial locality is improved because elements with consecutive memory addresses tend to be pulled up the memory hierarchy together.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-hierarchy] In computer architecture, the **memory hierarchy** separates computer storage into a hierarchy based on response time.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-hierarchy] Since response time, complexity, and capacity are related, the levels may also be distinguished by their performance and controlling technologies.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-hierarchy] Memory hierarchy affects performance in computer architectural design, algorithm predictions, and lower level programming constructs involving locality of reference.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-hierarchy] Designing for high performance requires considering the restrictions of the memory hierarchy, i.e. the size and capabilities of each component.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-hierarchy] Each of the various components can be viewed as part of a hierarchy of memories (*m*1, *m*2, ..., *mn*) in which each member mi is typically smaller and faster than the next highest member *m**i*+1 of the hierarchy.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-hierarchy] To limit waiting by higher levels, a lower level will respond by filling a buffer and then signaling for activating the transfer.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-hierarchy] This is a general memory hierarchy structuring.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-hierarchy] For example, a paging algorithm may be considered as a level for virtual memory when designing a computer architecture, and one can include a level of nearline storage between online and offline storage.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-hierarchy] The number of levels in the memory hierarchy and the performance at each level has increased over time.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-hierarchy] The type of memory or storage components also change historically.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-hierarchy] Some CPUs include additional levels of cache between L3 and memory.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-hierarchy] For example, the Haswell microarchitecture includes an L4 cache of 128 MB on mobile units.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-hierarchy] The lower levels of the hierarchy – from mass storage downwards – are also known as tiered storage.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-hierarchy] For example, always-on spinning disks are online, while spinning disks that spin down, such as massive arrays of idle disk (MAID), are nearline.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-hierarchy] Removable media such as tape cartridges that can be automatically loaded, as in a tape library, are nearline, while cartridges that must be manually loaded are offline.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-hierarchy] Most modern CPUs are so fast that, for most program workloads, the bottleneck is the locality of reference of memory accesses and the efficiency of the caching and memory transfer between different levels of the hierarchy.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-hierarchy] As a result, the CPU spends much of its time idling, waiting for memory I/O to complete.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-hierarchy] This is sometimes called the *space cost*, as a larger memory object is more likely to overflow a small and fast level and require use of a larger, slower level.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-hierarchy] The resulting load on memory use is known as *pressure* (respectively *register pressure*, *cache pressure*, and (main) *memory pressure*).
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-hierarchy] Modern programming languages mainly assume two levels of memory, main (*working*) memory and mass storage.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-hierarchy] The exception is the relatively low-level assembly language and in the inline assemblers of higher-level languages such as C where "prefetch" instructions can be used to preload the cache.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-hierarchy] Many programmers assume one level of memory.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-hierarchy] This works fine until the application hits a performance wall.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-hierarchy] At that point, the programmer needs to change the code's memory access patterns to that it works well with cache resources.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-hierarchy] A classic illustration of the effect of locality and caching is in the form of changing the order of iterating a three-dimensional array.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-hierarchy] *Computer Systems: A Programmer's Perspective* is a classic textbook that deals with this aspect of systems programming.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-hierarchy] Memory tiering is implemented on Linux as an extension to NUMA, where each memory provider has a CPU-less NUMA node with an appropriate "abstract distance" reflecting its performance.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-hierarchy] The existing scheme for migrating memory between NUMA nodes using "hotness" indicated by page faults is adapted to tiering by Huang Ying (Al Maruf's TPP scheme is not in Linux mainline).
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-hierarchy] It also uses a weighted-interleave allocation policy.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] In modern technology, random-access memory takes the form of integrated circuit (IC) chips with MOS (metal–oxide–semiconductor) memory cells.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] RAM is normally associated with volatile types of memory where stored information is lost if power is removed.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] The two main types of volatile random-access semiconductor memory are static random-access memory (SRAM) and dynamic random-access memory (DRAM).
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] Non-volatile RAM has also been developed and other types of non-volatile memories allow random access for read operations, but either do not allow write operations or have other kinds of limitations.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] These include most types of ROM and NOR flash memory.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] The use of semiconductor RAM dates back to 1965 when IBM introduced the monolithic (single-chip) 16-bit SP95 SRAM chip for their System/360 Model 95 computer, and Toshiba used bipolar DRAM memory cells for its 180-bit Toscal BC-1411 electronic calculator, both based on bipolar transistors.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] While it offered higher speeds than magnetic-core memory, bipolar DRAM could not compete with the lower price of the then-dominant magnetic-core memory.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] Robert Dennard invented modern DRAM architecture in which there's a single MOS transistor per capacitor.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] The first commercial DRAM IC chip, the 1K Intel 1103, was introduced in October 1970.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] Synchronous dynamic random-access memory (SDRAM) was reintroduced with the Samsung KM48SL2000 chip in 1992.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] Early computers used relays, mechanical counters or delay lines for main memory functions.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] Ultrasonic delay lines were serial devices which could only reproduce data in the order it was written.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] Drum memory could be expanded at relatively low cost but efficient retrieval of memory items requires knowledge of the physical layout of the drum to optimize speed.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] Latches built out of triode vacuum tubes, and later, out of discrete transistors, were used for smaller and faster memories such as registers.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] Such registers were relatively large and too costly to use for large amounts of data; generally, only a few dozen or few hundred bits of such memory could be provided.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] The first practical form of random-access memory was the Williams tube.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] It stored data as electrically charged spots on the face of a cathode-ray tube.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] Since the electron beam of the CRT could read and write the spots on the tube in any order, memory was random access.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] The capacity of the Williams tube was a few hundred to around a thousand bits, but it was much smaller, faster, and more power-efficient than using individual vacuum tube latches.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] Developed at the University of Manchester in England, the Williams tube provided the medium on which the first electronically stored program was implemented in the Manchester Baby computer, which first successfully ran a program on 21 June, 1948.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] In fact, rather than the Williams tube memory being designed for the Baby, the Baby was a testbed to demonstrate the reliability of the memory.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] Magnetic-core memory was invented in 1947 and developed up until the mid-1970s.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] It became a widespread form of random-access memory, relying on an array of magnetized rings.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] By changing the sense of each ring's magnetization, data could be stored with one bit stored per ring.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] Since every ring had a combination of address wires to select and read or write it, access to any memory location in any sequence was possible.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] Magnetic core memory was the standard form of computer memory until displaced by semiconductor memory in integrated circuits (ICs) during the early 1970s.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] Prior to the development of integrated read-only memory (ROM) circuits, *permanent* (or *read-only*) random-access memory was often constructed using diode matrices driven by address decoders, or specially wound core rope memory planes.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] Semiconductor memory appeared in the 1960s with bipolar memory, which used bipolar transistors.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] Although it was faster, it could not compete with the lower price of magnetic core memory.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] In 1957, Frosch and Derick manufactured the first silicon dioxide field-effect transistors at Bell Labs, the first transistors in which drain and source were adjacent at the surface.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] Subsequently, in 1960, a team demonstrated a working MOSFET at Bell Labs.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] This led to the development of metal–oxide–semiconductor (MOS) memory by John Schmidt at Fairchild Semiconductor in 1964.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] In addition to higher speeds, MOS semiconductor memory was cheaper and consumed less power than magnetic core memory.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] The development of silicon-gate MOS integrated circuit (MOS IC) technology by Federico Faggin at Fairchild in 1968 enabled the production of MOS memory chips.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] MOS memory overtook magnetic core memory as the dominant memory technology in the early 1970s.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] Integrated bipolar static random-access memory (SRAM) was invented by Robert H.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] Norman at Fairchild Semiconductor in 1963.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] It was followed by the development of MOS SRAM by John Schmidt at Fairchild in 1964.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] SRAM became an alternative to magnetic-core memory, but required six MOS transistors for each bit of data.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] Commercial use of SRAM began in 1965, when IBM introduced the SP95 memory chip for the System/360 Model 95.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] Dynamic random-access memory (DRAM) allowed replacement of a 4- or 6-transistor latch circuit by a single transistor for each memory bit, greatly increasing memory density at the cost of volatility.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] Data was stored in the tiny capacitance of each transistor and had to be periodically refreshed every few milliseconds before the charge could leak away.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] Toshiba's Toscal BC-1411 electronic calculator, which was introduced in 1965, used a form of capacitor bipolar DRAM, storing 180-bit data on discrete memory cells, consisting of germanium bipolar transistors and capacitors.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] Capacitors had also been used for earlier memory schemes, such as the drum of the Atanasoff–Berry Computer, the Williams tube and the Selectron tube.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] In 1966, Robert Dennard, while examining the characteristics of MOS technology, found it was capable of building capacitors, and that storing a charge or no charge on the MOS capacitor could represent the 1 and 0 of a bit, and the MOS transistor could control writing the charge to the capacitor.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] This led to his development of modern DRAM architecture for which there is a single MOS transistor per capacitor.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] In 1967, Dennard filed a patent under IBM for a single-transistor DRAM memory cell, based on MOS technology.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] The first commercial DRAM IC chip was the Intel 1103, which was manufactured on an 8 μm MOS process with a capacity of 1 kbit, and was released in 1970.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] The earliest DRAMs were often synchronized with the CPU clock and were used with early microprocessors.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] In the mid-1970s, DRAMs moved to the asynchronous design, but in the 1990s returned to synchronous operation.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] In 1992 Samsung released KM48SL2000, which had a capacity of 16 Mbit.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] The first commercial double data rate SDRAM was Samsung's 64 Mbit DDR SDRAM, released in June 1998.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] GDDR (graphics DDR) is a form of SGRAM (synchronous graphics RAM), which was first released by Samsung as a 16 Mbit memory chip in 1998.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] In general, the term *RAM* refers solely to solid-state memory devices, and more specifically the main memory in most computers.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] The two widely used forms of modern RAM are static RAM (SRAM) and dynamic RAM (DRAM).
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] In SRAM, a bit of data is stored using the state of a memory cell, typically using six MOSFETs.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] This form of RAM is more expensive to produce, but is generally faster and requires less static power than DRAM.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] In modern computers, SRAM is often used as cache memory for the CPU.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] DRAM stores a bit of data using a transistor and capacitor pair (typically a MOSFET and MOS capacitor, respectively), which together comprise a DRAM cell.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] The capacitor holds a high or low charge (1 or 0, respectively), and the transistor acts as a switch that lets the control circuitry on the chip read the capacitor's state of charge or change it.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] As this form of memory is less expensive to produce than static RAM, it is the predominant form of computer memory used in modern computers.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] Both static and dynamic RAM are considered *volatile*, as their state is lost when power is removed from the system.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] By contrast, read-only memory (ROM) stores data by permanently enabling or disabling selected transistors, such that the memory cannot be altered.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] Writable variants of ROM (such as EEPROM and NOR flash) share properties of both ROM and RAM, enabling data to persist without power and to be updated without requiring special equipment.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] ECC memory (which can be either SRAM or DRAM) includes special circuitry to detect and/or correct random faults (memory errors) in the stored data, using parity bits or error correction codes.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] The memory cell is the fundamental building block of computer memory.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] The memory cell is an electronic circuit that stores one bit of binary information.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] The cell can be set to store a logic 1 (high voltage level) and reset to store a logic 0 (low voltage level).
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] Its value is maintained until it is changed by the set/reset process.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] The value in the memory cell can be accessed by reading it.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] In SRAM, the memory cell is a type of flip-flop circuit, usually implemented using FETs.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] This means that SRAM requires very low power when not being accessed, but it is complex, expensive and has low storage density.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] A second type, DRAM, is based around a capacitor.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] Charging and discharging this capacitor can store a 1 or a 0 in the cell.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] However, the charge in this capacitor slowly leaks away and must be refreshed periodically.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] Because of this refresh process, DRAM uses more power, but it can achieve greater storage densities and lower unit costs compared to SRAM.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] To be useful, memory cells must be readable and writable.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] Within the RAM device, multiplexing and demultiplexing circuitry is used to select memory cells.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] Typically, a RAM device has a set of address lines $A_{0},A_{1},...A_{n}$ , and for each combination of bits that may be applied to these lines, a set of memory cells are selected.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] Due to this addressing, RAM devices virtually always have a memory capacity that is a power of two.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] Usually, several memory cells share the same address.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] For example, a 4-bit-wide RAM chip has four memory cells for each address.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] Often the width of the memory and that of the microprocessor are different; for a 32-bit microprocessor, eight 4-bit RAM chips would be needed.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] Often, more addresses are needed than can be provided by a single device.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] In that case, multiple devices are used, with external multiplexors used to select the device assigned to a specific address range.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] RAM is often byte addressable, although word-addressable RAM also exists.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] Many computer systems have a memory hierarchy consisting of processor registers, on-die SRAM caches, external caches, DRAM, memory paging systems and virtual memory or swap space on a SSD or hard drive.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] This entire pool of memory may be referred to as RAM from a programming perspective.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] The overall goal of using a memory hierarchy is to obtain the fastest possible average access time while minimizing the total cost of the entire memory system.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] In addition to serving as temporary storage and working space for the operating system and applications, RAM is used in numerous other ways.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] Most modern operating systems employ a method, known as virtual memory, of extending RAM capacity.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] A portion of the computer's hard drive or SSD is set aside for a *paging file* or a *scratch partition*, and the combination of physical RAM and the paging file forms the system's total memory.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] For example, if a computer has 2 GB of RAM and a 1 GB page file, the operating system has 3 GB total memory available to it.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] When the system runs low on physical memory, it can swap portions of RAM to the paging file to make room for new data.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] When the previously swapped information is needed again, another swap is performed to read the information back into RAM.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] Excessive use of this mechanism results in thrashing and generally hampers overall system performance, mainly because hard drives are far slower than RAM.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] Software can *partition* a portion of a computer's RAM, allowing it to act as a much faster hard drive that is called a RAM drive.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] A RAM drive typically loses the stored data when the computer is shut down.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] Sometimes, the contents of a relatively slow ROM chip are copied to RAM to allow for shorter access times.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] The ROM chip is then disabled while the initialized memory locations are switched in on the same block of addresses (often write-protected).
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] This process, sometimes called *shadowing*, is fairly common in both computers and embedded systems.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] As a common example, the BIOS in typical personal computers often has an option called "use shadow BIOS" or similar.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] When enabled, functions that rely on data from the BIOS's ROM instead use DRAM locations (most can also toggle shadowing of video card ROM or other ROM sections).
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] Free memory is reduced by the size of the shadowed ROMs.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] Depending on the system, this may not result in increased performance and may cause incompatibilities.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] For example, some hardware may be inaccessible to the operating system if shadow RAM is used.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] On some systems, the benefit may be hypothetical because the BIOS is not used after booting.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] Some virtual private network services utilize RAM servers to keep all runtime state, including session metadata and cryptographic material, in volatile memory.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] This is intended to improve security relative to disk-backed designs.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] In such a design, no data is written to hard drives; all information resides in volatile memory and is erased whenever the server is powered off or rebooted.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] The **memory wall** is the growing disparity of speed between CPU and the response time of memory (known as memory latency) outside the CPU chip.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] An important reason for this disparity is the limited communication bandwidth beyond chip boundaries.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] From 1986 to 2000, CPU speed improved at an annual rate of 55% while off-chip memory response time only improved at 10%.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] Given these trends, it was expected that memory latency would become an overwhelming bottleneck in computer performance.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] Another reason for the disparity is the enormous increase in the size of memory since the start of the PC revolution in the 1980s.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] Originally, PCs contained less than 1 megabyte of RAM, which often had a response time of 1 CPU clock cycle, meaning that it required 0 wait states.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] Larger memory units are inherently slower than smaller ones of the same type, simply because it takes longer for signals to traverse a larger circuit.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] Constructing a memory unit of many gigabytes with a response time of one clock cycle is difficult or impossible.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] Modern CPUs often still have 0 wait state cache memory, but, due to the bandwidth limitations of chip-to-chip communication, it must reside on the same chip as the CPU cores.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] It must also be constructed from static RAM, which is far more expensive than the dynamic RAM used for larger memories.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] CPU speed improvements slowed significantly, partly due to major physical barriers and partly because CPU designs have already hit the memory wall in some sense.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] Intel summarized these causes in a 2005 document.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] The RC delays in signal transmission were also noted in "Clock Rate versus IPC: The End of the Road for Conventional Microarchitectures" which projected a maximum of 12.5% average annual CPU performance improvement between 2000 and 2014.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] A different concept is the processor-memory performance gap, which can be addressed by 3D integrated circuits that reduce the distance between the control logic and memory cells that are further apart in a 2D chip.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] Memory subsystem design requires a focus on the gap, which is widening over time.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] The main method of bridging the gap is the use of caches; small amounts of high-speed memory that houses data associated with recent operations near the processor, speeding up access to this data in cases where they are called upon frequently.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] Multiple levels of caching have been developed to deal with the widening gap, and the performance of high-speed modern computers relies on evolving caching techniques.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] There can be up to a 53% difference between the growth in speed of processor and the lagging speed of main memory access.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/memory-wall] Fast, cheap, non-volatile solid state drives have replaced some functions formerly performed by RAM, such as holding certain data for immediate availability in server farms – 1 terabyte of SSD storage can be had for $200, while 1 TB of RAM would cost thousands of dollars.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/translation-lookaside-buffer] In computing and processor design, a **translation lookaside buffer** (**TLB**) is a memory cache that stores the recent translations of virtual memory addresses to physical memory addresses.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/translation-lookaside-buffer] It is used to reduce the time taken to access a user memory location.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/translation-lookaside-buffer] It can be called an address-translation cache.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/translation-lookaside-buffer] It is a part of the chip's memory-management unit (MMU).
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/translation-lookaside-buffer] A TLB may reside between the CPU and the CPU cache, between CPU cache and the main memory or between the different levels of the multi-level cache.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/translation-lookaside-buffer] The majority of desktop, laptop, and server processors include one or more TLBs in the memory-management hardware, and it is nearly always present in any processor that uses paged or segmented virtual memory.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/translation-lookaside-buffer] The TLB is sometimes implemented as content-addressable memory (CAM).
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/translation-lookaside-buffer] The CAM search key is the virtual address, and the search result is a physical address.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/translation-lookaside-buffer] If the requested address is present in the TLB, the CAM search yields a match quickly and the retrieved physical address can be used to access memory.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/translation-lookaside-buffer] If the requested address is not in the TLB, it is a miss, and the translation proceeds by looking up the page table in a process called a *page walk*.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/translation-lookaside-buffer] The page walk is time-consuming when compared to the processor speed, as it involves reading the contents of multiple memory locations and using them to compute the physical address.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/translation-lookaside-buffer] After the physical address is determined by the page walk, the virtual address to physical address mapping is entered into the TLB.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/translation-lookaside-buffer] The PowerPC 604, for example, has a two-way set-associative TLB for data loads and stores.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/translation-lookaside-buffer] Some processors have different instruction and data address TLBs.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/translation-lookaside-buffer] The virtual memory is the memory space as seen from a process; this space is often split into pages of a fixed size (in paged memory), or less commonly into segments of variable sizes (in segmented memory).
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/translation-lookaside-buffer] The page table, generally stored in main memory, keeps track of where the virtual pages are stored in the physical memory.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/translation-lookaside-buffer] This method uses two memory accesses (one for the page-table entry, one for the byte) to access a byte.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/translation-lookaside-buffer] First, the page table is looked up for the frame number.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/translation-lookaside-buffer] Second, the frame number with the page offset gives the actual address.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/translation-lookaside-buffer] Thus, any straightforward virtual memory scheme would have the effect of doubling the memory access time.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/translation-lookaside-buffer] Hence, the TLB is used to reduce the time taken to access the memory locations in the page-table method.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/translation-lookaside-buffer] The TLB is a cache of the page table, representing only a subset of the page-table contents.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/translation-lookaside-buffer] Referencing the physical memory addresses, a TLB may reside between the CPU and the CPU cache, between the CPU cache and primary storage memory, or between levels of a multi-level cache.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/translation-lookaside-buffer] The placement determines whether the cache uses physical or virtual addressing.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/translation-lookaside-buffer] If the cache is virtually addressed, requests are sent directly from the CPU to the cache, and the TLB is accessed only on a cache miss.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/translation-lookaside-buffer] If the cache is physically addressed, the CPU does a TLB lookup on every memory operation, and the resulting physical address is sent to the cache.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/translation-lookaside-buffer] In a Harvard architecture or modified Harvard architecture, a separate virtual address space or memory-access hardware may exist for instructions and data.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/translation-lookaside-buffer] This can lead to distinct TLBs for each access type, an *instruction translation lookaside buffer* (ITLB) and a *data translation lookaside buffer* (DTLB).
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/translation-lookaside-buffer] Various benefits have been demonstrated with separate data and instruction TLBs.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/translation-lookaside-buffer] The TLB can be used as a fast lookup hardware cache.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/translation-lookaside-buffer] Each entry in the TLB consists of two parts: a tag and a value.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/translation-lookaside-buffer] If the tag of the incoming virtual address matches the tag in the TLB, the corresponding value is returned.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/translation-lookaside-buffer] Since the TLB lookup is usually a part of the instruction pipeline, searches are fast and cause essentially no performance penalty.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/translation-lookaside-buffer] However, to be able to search within the instruction pipeline, the TLB has to be small.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/translation-lookaside-buffer] A common optimization for physically addressed caches is to perform the TLB lookup in parallel with the cache access.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/translation-lookaside-buffer] Upon each virtual memory reference, the hardware checks the TLB to see whether the page number is held therein.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/translation-lookaside-buffer] If yes, it is a TLB hit, and the translation is made.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/translation-lookaside-buffer] The frame number is returned and is used to access the memory.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/translation-lookaside-buffer] If the page number is not in the TLB, the page table must be checked.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/translation-lookaside-buffer] Depending on the CPU, this can be done automatically in hardware or using an interrupt to the operating system.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/translation-lookaside-buffer] When the frame number is obtained, it can be used to access the memory.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/translation-lookaside-buffer] In addition, we add the page number and frame number to the TLB, so that they will be found quickly on the next reference.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/translation-lookaside-buffer] If the TLB is already full, a suitable block must be selected for replacement.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/translation-lookaside-buffer] There are different replacement methods like *least recently used* (LRU), *first in, first out* (FIFO) etc.; see the address translation section in the cache article for more details about virtual addressing as it pertains to caches and TLBs.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/translation-lookaside-buffer] The CPU has to access main memory for an instruction-cache miss, data-cache miss, or TLB miss.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/translation-lookaside-buffer] The third case (the simplest one) is where the desired information itself actually *is* in a cache, but the information for virtual-to-physical translation is not in a TLB.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/translation-lookaside-buffer] These are all slow, due to the need to access a slower level of the memory hierarchy, so a well-functioning TLB is important.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/translation-lookaside-buffer] Indeed, a TLB miss can be more expensive than an instruction or data cache miss, due to the need for not just a load from main memory, but a page walk, requiring several memory accesses.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/translation-lookaside-buffer] The flowchart provided explains the working of a TLB.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/translation-lookaside-buffer] If it is a TLB miss, then the CPU checks the page table for the page table entry.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/translation-lookaside-buffer] If the *present bit* is set, then the page is in main memory, and the processor can retrieve the frame number from the page-table entry to form the physical address.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/translation-lookaside-buffer] The processor also updates the TLB to include the new page-table entry.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/translation-lookaside-buffer] Finally, if the present bit is not set, then the desired page is not in the main memory, and a page fault is issued.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/translation-lookaside-buffer] Then a page-fault interrupt is called, which executes the page-fault handling routine.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/translation-lookaside-buffer] If the page working set does not fit into the TLB, then TLB thrashing occurs, where frequent TLB misses occur, with each newly cached page displacing one that will soon be used again, degrading performance in exactly the same way as thrashing of the instruction or data cache does.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/translation-lookaside-buffer] TLB thrashing can occur even if instruction-cache or data-cache thrashing are not occurring, because these are cached in different-size units.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/translation-lookaside-buffer] Instructions and data are cached in small blocks (cache lines), not entire pages, but address lookup is done at the page level.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/translation-lookaside-buffer] Thus, even if the code and data working sets fit into cache, if the working sets are fragmented across many pages, the virtual-address working set may not fit into TLB, causing TLB thrashing.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/translation-lookaside-buffer] Appropriate sizing of the TLB thus requires considering not only the size of the corresponding instruction and data caches, but also how these are fragmented across multiple pages.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/translation-lookaside-buffer] Similar to caches, TLBs may have multiple levels.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/translation-lookaside-buffer] CPUs can be (and nowadays usually are) built with multiple TLBs, for example a small L1 TLB (potentially fully associative) that is extremely fast, and a larger L2 TLB that is somewhat slower.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/translation-lookaside-buffer] When instruction-TLB (ITLB) and data-TLB (DTLB) are used, a CPU can have three (ITLB1, DTLB1, TLB2) or four TLBs.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/translation-lookaside-buffer] Some TLBs may have separate sections for small pages and huge pages.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/translation-lookaside-buffer] For example, Intel Skylake microarchitecture separates the TLB entries for 1 GiB pages from those for 4 KiB/2 MiB pages.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/translation-lookaside-buffer] The MIPS architecture specifies a software-managed TLB.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/translation-lookaside-buffer] The SPARC V9 architecture allows an implementation of SPARC V9 to have no MMU, an MMU with a software-managed TLB, or an MMU with a hardware-managed TLB, and the UltraSPARC Architecture 2005 specifies a software-managed TLB.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/translation-lookaside-buffer] The Itanium architecture provides an option of using either software- or hardware-managed TLBs.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/translation-lookaside-buffer] The Alpha architecture has a firmware-managed TLB, with the TLB miss handling code being in PALcode, rather than in the operating system.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/translation-lookaside-buffer] The average effective memory cycle rate is defined as $m+(1-p)h+pm$ cycles, where m is the number of cycles required for a memory read, p is the miss rate, and h is the hit time in cycles.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/translation-lookaside-buffer] If a TLB hit takes 1 clock cycle, a miss takes 30 clock cycles, a memory read takes 30 clock cycles, and the miss rate is 1%, the effective memory cycle rate is an average of $30+0.99\times 1+0.01\times 30$ (31.29 clock cycles per memory access).
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/translation-lookaside-buffer] On an address-space switch, as occurs when context switching between processes (but not between threads), some TLB entries can become invalid, since the virtual-to-physical mapping is different.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/translation-lookaside-buffer] The simplest strategy to deal with this is to completely flush the TLB.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/translation-lookaside-buffer] This means that after a switch, the TLB is empty, and *any* memory reference will be a miss, so it will be some time before things are running back at full speed.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/translation-lookaside-buffer] Newer CPUs use more effective strategies marking which process an entry is for.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/translation-lookaside-buffer] This means that if a second process runs for only a short time and jumps back to a first process, the TLB may still have valid entries, saving the time to reload them.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/translation-lookaside-buffer] Other strategies avoid flushing the TLB on a context switch: (a) A single address space operating system uses the same virtual-to-physical mapping for all processes.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/translation-lookaside-buffer] (b) Some CPUs have a process ID register, and the hardware uses TLB entries only if they match the current process ID.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/translation-lookaside-buffer] For example, in the Alpha 21264, each TLB entry is tagged with an *address space number* (ASN), and only TLB entries with an ASN matching the current task are considered valid.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/translation-lookaside-buffer] Since the 2010 Westmere microarchitecture Intel 64 processors also support 12-bit *process-context identifiers* (PCIDs), which allow retaining TLB entries for multiple linear-address spaces, with only those that match the current PCID being used for address translation.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/translation-lookaside-buffer] While selective flushing of the TLB is an option in software-managed TLBs, the only option in some hardware TLBs (for example, the TLB in the Intel 80386) is the complete flushing of the TLB on an address-space switch.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/translation-lookaside-buffer] Other hardware TLBs (for example, the TLB in the Intel 80486 and later x86 processors, and the TLB in ARM processors) allow the flushing of individual entries from the TLB indexed by virtual address.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/translation-lookaside-buffer] Flushing of the TLB can be an important security mechanism for memory isolation between processes to ensure a process can't access data stored in memory pages of another process.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/translation-lookaside-buffer] Memory isolation is especially critical during switches between the privileged operating system kernel process and the user processes – as was highlighted by the Meltdown security vulnerability.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/translation-lookaside-buffer] Mitigation strategies such as kernel page-table isolation (KPTI) rely heavily on performance-impacting TLB flushes and benefit greatly from hardware-enabled selective TLB entry management such as PCID.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/translation-lookaside-buffer] With the advent of virtualization for server consolidation, a lot of effort has gone into making the x86 architecture easier to virtualize and to ensure better performance of virtual machines on x86 hardware.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/translation-lookaside-buffer] Normally, entries in the x86 TLBs are not associated with a particular address space; they implicitly refer to the current address space.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/translation-lookaside-buffer] Hence, every time there is a change in address space, such as a context switch, the entire TLB has to be flushed.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/translation-lookaside-buffer] Maintaining a tag that associates each TLB entry with an address space in software and comparing this tag during TLB lookup and TLB flush is very expensive, especially since the x86 TLB is designed to operate with very low latency and completely in hardware.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/translation-lookaside-buffer] In 2008, both Intel (Nehalem) and AMD (SVM) have introduced tags as part of the TLB entry and dedicated hardware that checks the tag during lookup.
[src:memory-hierarchy-design/translation-lookaside-buffer] Not all operating systems made full use of these tags immediately, but Linux 4.14 started using them to identify recently used address spaces, since the 12-bits PCIDs (4095 different values) are insufficient for all tasks running on a given CPU.
